1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,500
[♪]

2
00:00:13,882 --> 00:00:15,342
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

3
00:00:15,425 --> 00:00:16,965
[THUNDER CRASHING]

4
00:00:17,052 --> 00:00:19,172
[LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING]

5
00:00:22,766 --> 00:00:24,436
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

6
00:00:27,396 --> 00:00:29,356
You’re talkin’
through your ear,
Snoose.

7
00:00:29,481 --> 00:00:31,451
The Middle Fork
and the Feather River
have been worked clean.

8
00:00:31,525 --> 00:00:34,025
There ain’t no gold there.
You sayin’ I’m lyin’, Amos?

9
00:00:34,152 --> 00:00:35,652
He’s not sayin’ that,
Snoose.

10
00:00:35,737 --> 00:00:37,197
Stupid poundin’
horseshoes.

11
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:39,910
A couple brothers washed out
$1100 in one pan.

12
00:00:40,033 --> 00:00:42,363
That is an old story,
Snoose, and it ain’t true.

13
00:00:42,452 --> 00:00:44,952
I had my first claim
on the Feather.
It was clean then.

14
00:00:45,038 --> 00:00:47,458
You know, Jimmy,
any gold you got
belonged to somebody else.

15
00:00:47,541 --> 00:00:50,421
Snoose,
stop talkin’ like that.
Jimmy’s no thief.

16
00:00:50,544 --> 00:00:54,584
He hides dust in the collar
of that ugly dog of his.
I seen him do it.

17
00:00:54,715 --> 00:00:55,675
Come on!

18
00:00:55,757 --> 00:00:57,887
[MUSIC STOPS]

19
00:00:57,968 --> 00:00:59,928
Oh, not in here.
Now knock it off!

20
00:01:02,556 --> 00:01:04,056
SOPHIE: Stop!

21
00:01:04,182 --> 00:01:06,472
I’m sorry, Miss Sophie.
You all right?

22
00:01:06,560 --> 00:01:07,900
Ow! You bit me!

23
00:01:07,978 --> 00:01:09,228
Get outside! Now get out!

24
00:01:09,354 --> 00:01:11,734
Come on, Snoose, come on!
Give it to me!

25
00:01:11,857 --> 00:01:13,357
Come on,
you son of a gun!

26
00:01:13,442 --> 00:01:14,772
[JIMMY YELLING]

27
00:01:14,901 --> 00:01:16,861
JIMMY: Snoose, I’m gonna
eat your liver.

28
00:01:16,945 --> 00:01:18,615
[SNOOSE AND JIMMY YELLING]

29
00:01:26,788 --> 00:01:28,038
Stop!

30
00:01:30,876 --> 00:01:34,086
Uh, may I help you?

31
00:01:35,422 --> 00:01:37,882
Is this Lucky Diggins?

32
00:01:37,966 --> 00:01:39,506
Yes, it is.

33
00:01:39,593 --> 00:01:42,633
This is Scatter’s Saloon.
I’m Mr. Scatter.

34
00:01:42,763 --> 00:01:44,423
You are?

35
00:01:44,556 --> 00:01:47,556
I’m Mrs. Arvella Whipple
from Buttonfields,
Massachusetts.

36
00:01:47,642 --> 00:01:52,432
We answered your advertisement
in the <i>San Francisco Chronicle
</i> to run your boardinghouse.

37
00:01:52,564 --> 00:01:53,934
We’re here.

38
00:01:55,108 --> 00:01:58,908
Um, ahem, so you are.

39
00:01:58,987 --> 00:02:00,447
I didn’t expect you so soon,
Mrs. Whipple,

40
00:02:00,572 --> 00:02:02,282
and I didn’t expect
you’d be bringing your family.

41
00:02:02,407 --> 00:02:04,617
You think
I’d discard them somewhere?

42
00:02:04,743 --> 00:02:06,703
No.

43
00:02:06,787 --> 00:02:08,127
Where’s your husband,
Mrs. Whipple?

44
00:02:08,205 --> 00:02:11,295
Dead. May I please
see the boardinghouse?

45
00:02:12,584 --> 00:02:13,624
Oh.

46
00:02:16,046 --> 00:02:18,336
Right this way.
Come, children.

47
00:02:21,760 --> 00:02:24,310
This is it.

48
00:02:24,429 --> 00:02:26,519
This isn’t
a boardinghouse,
it’s a tent.

49
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:28,150
It’s a boarding tent.

50
00:02:28,266 --> 00:02:30,766
About the only houses
in Lucky Diggins
are outhouses.

51
00:02:30,852 --> 00:02:32,512
[LAUGHING]

52
00:02:32,646 --> 00:02:34,396
Go on, children.
Go on in.

53
00:02:34,481 --> 00:02:36,611
We’re buildin’
a real boardinghouse, though.

54
00:02:36,691 --> 00:02:39,691
We only have three boarders
at the present time.

55
00:02:39,820 --> 00:02:41,580
I’ve been tryin’
to get more,

56
00:02:41,655 --> 00:02:44,235
but with some of the miners
wantin’ to be closer
to the river,

57
00:02:44,324 --> 00:02:47,364
well, I haven’t had
much luck so far.

58
00:02:47,494 --> 00:02:49,324
I can see why.

59
00:02:51,623 --> 00:02:53,123
SCATTER: Yeah.

60
00:02:53,208 --> 00:02:57,338
If you just follow me outside,
there’s a tent for you.

61
00:02:57,420 --> 00:03:00,430
It might be a bit small
for four.

62
00:03:00,507 --> 00:03:02,047
The pay’s $10 a month.

63
00:03:02,175 --> 00:03:04,345
Could be more if your
cooking’s any good.
It isn’t.

64
00:03:04,469 --> 00:03:07,139
This tent is too small
for four squirrels,
Mr. Scatter.

65
00:03:07,222 --> 00:03:09,722
I trust you’ll replace it
with a larger one
in the morning.

66
00:03:09,850 --> 00:03:12,860
Huh.
Go in, quick, quick.

67
00:03:12,936 --> 00:03:16,646
We’re not actually
really staying here,
are we, Mama?

68
00:03:16,731 --> 00:03:18,521
Of course we are,
California.

69
00:03:18,608 --> 00:03:22,028
We didn’t come all this way
just to turn around
and go back.

70
00:03:23,822 --> 00:03:26,692
Just wait until morning,
children.

71
00:03:26,825 --> 00:03:28,575
I bet it’s a fine place.

72
00:03:33,039 --> 00:03:35,049
[MEN CHATTERING]

73
00:03:37,919 --> 00:03:39,629
[HORSES NEIGHING]

74
00:03:47,053 --> 00:03:48,513
[BLEATING]

75
00:03:54,060 --> 00:03:55,690
[GRUNTING]

76
00:03:57,564 --> 00:04:00,774
You know,
I haven’t seen any riverbeds
paved with gold, Mama,

77
00:04:00,901 --> 00:04:03,741
or fruit hanging
from every tree.

78
00:04:03,820 --> 00:04:07,080
All I see is mud
and leaky tents

79
00:04:07,198 --> 00:04:10,158
and more dirty men
than I’ve ever seen
in my entire life.

80
00:04:10,243 --> 00:04:14,453
Well, look again, California.
You just open your eyes,
you might like it.

81
00:04:14,581 --> 00:04:15,921
I’ll never like it.

82
00:04:16,041 --> 00:04:17,881
If Pa were here,
he’d see how horrible it was

83
00:04:17,959 --> 00:04:19,919
and he’d take us home
immediately.

84
00:04:20,045 --> 00:04:23,045
We are home,
and we’re gonna be happy here.

85
00:04:23,131 --> 00:04:25,631
Your pa would see
how beautiful it is.

86
00:04:25,759 --> 00:04:28,889
If you can’t see it,
don’t spoil it
for the rest of us.

87
00:04:28,970 --> 00:04:31,640
Yeah, California.
I like it here.

88
00:04:31,765 --> 00:04:34,185
I like it here too.

89
00:04:36,603 --> 00:04:38,433
It’s awful.

90
00:04:43,109 --> 00:04:44,869
CALIFORNIA:
We’ve been here
over two weeks

91
00:04:44,945 --> 00:04:47,155
and all we’ve done
is work and work.

92
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:50,950
[SIGHS] Do you know
why Mr. Scatter
started this town?

93
00:04:51,034 --> 00:04:52,404
This is where his mule died.

94
00:04:52,494 --> 00:04:55,454
I mean, no decent town
ever started that way.

95
00:04:55,538 --> 00:04:57,418
And now that
all the mud is gone,

96
00:04:57,499 --> 00:05:00,629
there’s nothing but dust
covering everything.

97
00:05:00,752 --> 00:05:01,962
[SIGHS]

98
00:05:02,087 --> 00:05:04,007
I mean, are these
the wonderful...

99
00:05:04,130 --> 00:05:06,180
Possibilities
you promised us?

100
00:05:06,299 --> 00:05:08,139
[BUTTE AND PRAIRIE LAUGHING]

101
00:05:08,259 --> 00:05:10,309
What you dumb
sons of bitches
don’t know

102
00:05:10,387 --> 00:05:12,637
is gold’s not just
in the streams.
It’s in the hills too.

103
00:05:12,722 --> 00:05:15,262
There’ll be no swearing
in here, Mr. McGrath.
My children are present.

104
00:05:15,350 --> 00:05:18,820
You should have stayed
in Massachusetts,
then, ma’am.

105
00:05:18,895 --> 00:05:22,565
Apologize to Mrs. Whipple,
Snoose.

106
00:05:22,649 --> 00:05:26,489
CARROTS: I don’t think
he fathoms the concept
of table manners, ma’am.

107
00:05:26,611 --> 00:05:30,111
The truth is, the easy gold
is gone, and we all know it.

108
00:05:30,198 --> 00:05:32,078
JIMMY: It don’t matter
if it’s easy or hard.

109
00:05:32,158 --> 00:05:35,208
There’s gold out there
waitin’ to be found.
It is needin’ to be found.

110
00:05:35,328 --> 00:05:37,708
Now, we seen the elephant,
and we ain’t blinked.

111
00:05:37,831 --> 00:05:41,421
And there ain’t many men
that can say that,
nor dog neither. Hallelujah.

112
00:05:41,501 --> 00:05:44,211
ALL: Hallelujah!
MAN: Praise God.

113
00:05:44,337 --> 00:05:46,177
SNOOSE: You know, I dreamed
I hit pay dirt last night.

114
00:05:46,297 --> 00:05:48,547
JIMMY: If you dream it,
it comes true.

115
00:05:48,675 --> 00:05:49,635
SNOOSE: Mule poop.

116
00:05:49,718 --> 00:05:51,598
[HORSE NEIGHING]

117
00:05:54,806 --> 00:05:56,056
Excuse me.

118
00:05:56,182 --> 00:05:58,852
Uh, I’ve seen you reading,
California.

119
00:05:58,935 --> 00:06:00,975
You like books?

120
00:06:01,062 --> 00:06:02,562
I love books.

121
00:06:03,690 --> 00:06:06,490
But my mama
only let me bring 10,

122
00:06:06,568 --> 00:06:09,368
and I’ve read them
so many times
the pages are falling out.

123
00:06:09,446 --> 00:06:12,326
[LAUGHS]
You really do like to read.

124
00:06:12,407 --> 00:06:14,407
My name’s Joshua Beale,

125
00:06:14,534 --> 00:06:17,704
but everyone here
calls me Carrots
on account of my hair.

126
00:06:21,791 --> 00:06:23,871
I hate my name too.

127
00:06:24,002 --> 00:06:25,752
My mama always dreamed
of going west,

128
00:06:25,879 --> 00:06:28,509
and so she named us all
after things out here.

129
00:06:28,590 --> 00:06:31,560
My brother is Butte
and my sister is Prairie,

130
00:06:31,634 --> 00:06:33,594
and I have
the horrible misfortune

131
00:06:33,720 --> 00:06:36,480
of being called
California Morning.

132
00:06:36,556 --> 00:06:38,056
[CHUCKLES]

133
00:06:38,183 --> 00:06:40,853
So, what are you
doing out here?

134
00:06:40,935 --> 00:06:42,815
Well, uh,

135
00:06:42,896 --> 00:06:46,276
oh, I was a lawyer

136
00:06:46,399 --> 00:06:48,149
with no clients.

137
00:06:48,234 --> 00:06:51,904
We, um‐‐ Well, I decided
to make my fortune
in the gold fields,

138
00:06:51,988 --> 00:06:54,038
but I haven’t had
much luck yet.

139
00:06:54,115 --> 00:06:57,155
What does
"seeing the elephant" mean?

140
00:06:57,243 --> 00:07:00,823
Well, it means everything
about the gold rush.

141
00:07:01,998 --> 00:07:04,418
The ordeal of getting here,

142
00:07:04,501 --> 00:07:07,171
leaving your family
to dig for gold.

143
00:07:07,253 --> 00:07:10,923
The joy of finding
even the tiniest nugget

144
00:07:11,049 --> 00:07:12,719
and the heartbreak of not.

145
00:07:14,260 --> 00:07:16,680
I wonder
what my pa would think
of this place.

146
00:07:18,014 --> 00:07:22,684
I miss him so much sometimes
that it aches inside.

147
00:07:24,270 --> 00:07:26,570
I think my ma’s forgotten
all about him.

148
00:07:30,944 --> 00:07:32,694
That’s not likely, miss.

149
00:07:39,953 --> 00:07:42,203
SNOOSE:
Hallelujah!

150
00:07:42,288 --> 00:07:44,458
Is anyone minding the store?

151
00:07:45,792 --> 00:07:46,952
Sophie.

152
00:07:48,837 --> 00:07:51,587
I’d like two pounds
of bear fat,
a quart of vinegar

153
00:07:51,673 --> 00:07:53,423
and a sack of flour, please.

154
00:07:54,634 --> 00:07:57,344
You get used to
this dust pit yet?

155
00:07:57,470 --> 00:08:00,690
Well, not entirely,
but I like it here.

156
00:08:00,807 --> 00:08:05,897
You like runnin’
Scatter’s broken‐down,
smelly old boardinghouse?

157
00:08:05,979 --> 00:08:07,649
It’s honest work.

158
00:08:07,772 --> 00:08:08,812
Bull.

159
00:08:08,898 --> 00:08:11,818
Everybody comes for gold.

160
00:08:11,943 --> 00:08:13,483
I didn’t.

161
00:08:13,570 --> 00:08:16,330
I came here
to give my family
a better life.

162
00:08:16,447 --> 00:08:19,497
And you picked
this mule‐turd town
to follow your dream?

163
00:08:24,289 --> 00:08:25,999
How’d your husband die?

164
00:08:28,001 --> 00:08:29,551
Pneumonia.

165
00:08:29,669 --> 00:08:31,169
Too bad.

166
00:08:31,296 --> 00:08:35,386
Well, plenty of men
in Lucky Diggins
are lookin’ for wives,

167
00:08:35,508 --> 00:08:37,098
and they’re not lookin’
at me.

168
00:08:37,177 --> 00:08:39,217
Well, they best not
look at me, either.

169
00:08:39,345 --> 00:08:41,845
How much?
Five dollars.

170
00:08:44,517 --> 00:08:46,857
I’ll have Jonas
take it out of your wages.

171
00:08:48,021 --> 00:08:49,611
Thank you.

172
00:08:54,027 --> 00:08:57,947
CALIFORNIA:
<i>Dear Gram and Grampop,
well, we’re here.</i>

173
00:08:58,031 --> 00:09:01,961
<i>There’s no school,
no church and no library.</i>

174
00:09:02,035 --> 00:09:04,035
<i>I’m almost 14
and should not have to live</i>

175
00:09:04,120 --> 00:09:07,500
<i>in a place
where people will die
to see elephants.</i>

176
00:09:07,582 --> 00:09:12,662
<i>Mama thinks Lucky Diggins
is heaven, but I think
it’s the other place.</i>

177
00:09:15,131 --> 00:09:19,751
"...thou mayst overpower,
for God made women weak,
and..."

178
00:09:19,886 --> 00:09:21,556
What am I supposed to do
with this?

179
00:09:21,679 --> 00:09:23,979
Well, there’s meat
for to feed us
and our boarders,

180
00:09:24,057 --> 00:09:26,517
so you’ve gotta
shoot some rabbits
and squirrels.

181
00:09:26,601 --> 00:09:28,651
Me? I’m not even
a good shot.

182
00:09:28,728 --> 00:09:30,688
Isn’t this a job for Butte?

183
00:09:30,772 --> 00:09:33,482
Butte has a job
at Mr. Scatter’s,
and meat’s too expensive,

184
00:09:33,566 --> 00:09:35,316
so here you go.

185
00:09:35,401 --> 00:09:38,401
[SIGHS] You know,
all I do is work around here.

186
00:09:38,529 --> 00:09:40,329
Now I have to slay
little animals?

187
00:09:40,406 --> 00:09:42,866
I don’t even have enough time
to read anymore.

188
00:09:47,413 --> 00:09:48,783
[EXCLAIMS]

189
00:09:50,416 --> 00:09:51,626
All right.

190
00:09:51,751 --> 00:09:54,501
I can pan for gold.
I can do that.

191
00:09:55,338 --> 00:09:56,968
That’s a good idea.

192
00:09:57,090 --> 00:09:59,470
All you have to do
is dig up about a ton
of dirt a day,

193
00:09:59,592 --> 00:10:01,462
then squat knee‐deep
in ice‐cold water

194
00:10:01,594 --> 00:10:04,054
and sift through the dirt
till your arms are numb.

195
00:10:12,021 --> 00:10:13,061
[SIGHS]

196
00:10:14,107 --> 00:10:15,857
Don’t forget this.

197
00:10:15,942 --> 00:10:18,612
Pick some blueberries,
like your pa liked.

198
00:10:27,829 --> 00:10:29,959
This ain’t what I expected,
Bernard.

199
00:10:31,791 --> 00:10:34,121
"...since the time
of Abraham downwards,

200
00:10:34,252 --> 00:10:38,172
"there have been women
who have devoted
their thoughts to heaven,

201
00:10:38,298 --> 00:10:41,008
"and their actions
to the works of kindness
of men,

202
00:10:41,134 --> 00:10:46,134
"tending the sick,
feeding the hungry,
and relieving the distressed.

203
00:10:46,222 --> 00:10:51,012
And among these
will I, Rebecca, be numbered."

204
00:11:08,453 --> 00:11:09,663
[SCREAMS]

205
00:11:17,628 --> 00:11:19,128
At first I thought
it was a grizzly,

206
00:11:19,213 --> 00:11:22,463
but when I got closer,
I saw that it was a person.

207
00:11:22,550 --> 00:11:25,930
I think it was an Indian.
I’m sure he went off
to get the rest of his tribe.

208
00:11:26,012 --> 00:11:28,012
We just can’t
stay here anymore, Mama.

209
00:11:28,097 --> 00:11:30,057
I know, I know.

210
00:11:30,183 --> 00:11:33,813
We might be captured
and have to live on acorns
and crushed grasshoppers.

211
00:11:33,895 --> 00:11:37,645
Well, we might.
You are all
imagination and no sense.

212
00:11:37,732 --> 00:11:39,352
But, Mama, I really did...

213
00:11:39,442 --> 00:11:41,482
"But, Mama" nothing.
Lord, you are
the spookiest child.

214
00:11:41,569 --> 00:11:43,449
What’s to become of you?

215
00:11:43,529 --> 00:11:46,409
Every tub has to learn
how to stand
on its own bottom sometimes.

216
00:11:46,532 --> 00:11:49,322
Now, as for you,
no meat, no supper.

217
00:11:49,410 --> 00:11:50,750
I’ll starve.

218
00:11:50,870 --> 00:11:53,380
That’s the best reason
I know to find meat.

219
00:11:53,456 --> 00:11:54,706
[SIGHS]

220
00:11:56,417 --> 00:11:58,257
California Whipple!

221
00:12:03,633 --> 00:12:05,673
CALIFORNIA: <i>Mama’s gotten
mean as a skunk.</i>

222
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:09,850
<i>This may be my last letter,
because she’s starving me
to death.</i>

223
00:12:09,931 --> 00:12:13,101
Food for the mind
and food for the body.

224
00:12:13,226 --> 00:12:14,686
Oh, thank you, Mr. Beale.

225
00:12:16,729 --> 00:12:18,479
I’ll return them
as soon as I read them.

226
00:12:18,564 --> 00:12:21,564
Oh, they’re just my law books.
You can keep ’em.

227
00:12:23,069 --> 00:12:25,619
California,
I’ll be leaving soon.

228
00:12:25,738 --> 00:12:28,328
Can I go with you?
[LAUGHING] No, you can’t.

229
00:12:28,408 --> 00:12:30,538
Besides, your mama needs you.

230
00:12:30,618 --> 00:12:34,878
She doesn’t need me at all,
except to do work.

231
00:12:36,374 --> 00:12:38,584
You better take
a grown‐up look, girl.

232
00:12:38,709 --> 00:12:42,179
Your mama does need you,
and for a lot more than work.

233
00:12:42,255 --> 00:12:46,045
You ought to be grateful
you can take care of her.

234
00:12:46,134 --> 00:12:49,594
You don’t know
what it feels like
when you can’t.

235
00:12:53,766 --> 00:12:58,776
Now, look, you eat that there
before I get in trouble
for stealing it.

236
00:13:04,110 --> 00:13:05,820
Goodbye, California.

237
00:13:06,863 --> 00:13:07,903
Bye.

238
00:13:14,912 --> 00:13:16,702
CALIFORNIA: I’m sure
it was an Indian,

239
00:13:16,789 --> 00:13:19,799
but he was very small and...

240
00:13:19,917 --> 00:13:21,707
Maybe it was
a prehistoric man

241
00:13:21,794 --> 00:13:24,294
and I’m the first
<i>Homo sapien</i> to see him.

242
00:13:24,380 --> 00:13:27,010
Oh, God.
Butte, don’t go to sleep.

243
00:13:27,133 --> 00:13:29,133
What do you think?

244
00:13:29,260 --> 00:13:30,970
He was an Indian.

245
00:13:31,053 --> 00:13:33,513
They love to scalp
little girls.

246
00:13:33,639 --> 00:13:35,689
The lantern attracts them.

247
00:13:35,808 --> 00:13:37,308
It’s God’s truth.

248
00:13:47,153 --> 00:13:48,193
[GUN FIRING]

249
00:13:48,321 --> 00:13:49,781
[GASPS] What is that?

250
00:13:53,242 --> 00:13:55,452
MAN 1: What was that?
MAN 2: I was sleepin’.

251
00:13:55,536 --> 00:13:57,076
[ALL CHATTERING]

252
00:14:01,417 --> 00:14:04,797
Carrots done gone
and shot himself
in the head.

253
00:14:04,879 --> 00:14:06,629
SCATTER: He’s dead.
[CRYING] No!

254
00:14:06,714 --> 00:14:08,714
MAN: Bless us, O Lord.

255
00:14:08,841 --> 00:14:12,211
[SOBS]
No, no! No, no, no.
It’s best not to look.

256
00:14:13,346 --> 00:14:15,306
[CRYING] But he was my friend.

257
00:14:16,682 --> 00:14:18,802
Why would he do
something like that?

258
00:14:18,893 --> 00:14:22,063
Didn’t find no gold is why.
Wife and six kids in Ohio.

259
00:14:22,188 --> 00:14:23,988
AMOS: Damn shame.

260
00:14:24,065 --> 00:14:26,945
Well, why is gold
so important?

261
00:14:27,026 --> 00:14:29,026
I hate this town.
I hate it, it’s horrible.

262
00:14:29,111 --> 00:14:30,521
Lucy...
At least he saw
the elephant.

263
00:14:30,613 --> 00:14:32,823
Wait, let her go.
Why?

264
00:14:32,907 --> 00:14:35,867
I need your help
preparin’ the body.

265
00:14:35,952 --> 00:14:38,992
Miners are too squeamish
to mess with stiffs.

266
00:14:39,872 --> 00:14:42,202
You ever done it before?

267
00:14:42,333 --> 00:14:43,833
My husband.

268
00:14:51,133 --> 00:14:53,883
So did you actually see
the body and the blood?

269
00:14:54,011 --> 00:14:56,051
He wasn’t a barn rat, Butte.

270
00:14:56,180 --> 00:14:57,770
[SIGHS]

271
00:14:57,890 --> 00:15:00,060
You know, getting buried
in a box doesn’t make you rot
any slower.

272
00:15:00,142 --> 00:15:02,312
What do you suppose
Pa looks like now?

273
00:15:02,395 --> 00:15:03,605
I mean, do you think‐‐?

274
00:15:03,729 --> 00:15:05,529
How could you think
of him like that?

275
00:15:05,606 --> 00:15:09,196
Sometimes I think
of scary things
to practice for being brave.

276
00:15:09,277 --> 00:15:11,567
I’m the only man
in the family
now that Pa’s dead.

277
00:15:11,696 --> 00:15:13,786
Yeah, well,
you’re not Pa, okay?

278
00:15:13,906 --> 00:15:17,246
I think of him
as being sweet and kind,
not like you.

279
00:15:41,767 --> 00:15:42,977
[SIGHS]

280
00:15:45,396 --> 00:15:47,356
[♪]

281
00:16:25,686 --> 00:16:26,896
[TWIG SNAPS]

282
00:16:30,316 --> 00:16:31,106
Who are you?

283
00:16:31,192 --> 00:16:34,482
Annie Flagg my name.
It’s mine.

284
00:16:36,280 --> 00:16:39,330
I’m California Whipple.
I live in Lucky Diggins.

285
00:16:42,286 --> 00:16:45,126
Were you the one watching me
in the meadow?

286
00:16:46,207 --> 00:16:48,167
What’s that red thing there?

287
00:16:49,543 --> 00:16:51,663
A book.

288
00:16:51,796 --> 00:16:53,426
<i>Ivanhoe.
</i> Have you ever read it?

289
00:16:55,257 --> 00:16:56,847
Can’t read.

290
00:16:56,926 --> 00:17:00,556
You can come in
if you want.

291
00:17:07,687 --> 00:17:10,527
You made this hut?

292
00:17:13,067 --> 00:17:15,357
And you made all these things?

293
00:17:17,863 --> 00:17:19,533
Oh, what’s that?

294
00:17:20,616 --> 00:17:22,956
That a bone whistle.

295
00:17:23,035 --> 00:17:25,365
You just blow
right there.

296
00:17:26,872 --> 00:17:28,242
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

297
00:17:28,374 --> 00:17:29,374
[LAUGHS]

298
00:17:30,876 --> 00:17:32,586
[GROWLING]

299
00:17:32,712 --> 00:17:34,002
Here a slip‐noose snare.

300
00:17:34,088 --> 00:17:36,888
Catch go slow.
Gun no good.

301
00:17:38,300 --> 00:17:40,970
You wanna catch ’em,
I’ll show you where to look.

302
00:17:42,555 --> 00:17:44,475
[SNARLING]

303
00:17:47,309 --> 00:17:49,439
[WOLF GROWLING LOUDLY]
[GASPS]

304
00:17:52,398 --> 00:17:53,568
Huh.

305
00:17:59,238 --> 00:18:00,278
Hungry.

306
00:18:24,597 --> 00:18:26,887
There’s no buckshot.

307
00:18:26,974 --> 00:18:28,844
Now, how did you
manage that?

308
00:18:28,934 --> 00:18:31,394
Well, it’s better
without a shotgun, Mama.

309
00:18:31,479 --> 00:18:34,779
A slip noose is best
for a go‐slower...
A possum.

310
00:18:34,857 --> 00:18:38,947
And a drop cage
for the prairie chickens.
You just use corn for bait.

311
00:18:39,862 --> 00:18:41,772
Annie taught me, Mama.

312
00:18:41,906 --> 00:18:45,826
She lives in this stick house
that she built all by herself
in the woods.

313
00:18:45,951 --> 00:18:48,451
And she also taught me
how to speak to crows.

314
00:18:48,537 --> 00:18:52,037
She calls them sky‐scratch
because of their
scratchy voice.

315
00:18:52,124 --> 00:18:55,584
[MIMICKING CROW]

316
00:18:55,669 --> 00:18:58,219
And she has
this huge white wolf
that she feeds bones to,

317
00:18:58,297 --> 00:18:59,507
Silver Dog.

318
00:18:59,632 --> 00:19:00,962
Where do you come from?

319
00:19:01,091 --> 00:19:02,961
You don’t believe me?

320
00:19:03,093 --> 00:19:07,173
Well, first it was Indians
and grizzlies
and now it’s a forest child.

321
00:19:07,306 --> 00:19:11,226
Would you please
live in this world
for a moment?

322
00:19:11,310 --> 00:19:15,360
Mr. Scatter just told me
that my bread is as hard
as tree bark and not as tasty,

323
00:19:15,481 --> 00:19:17,491
so I’d like you
to do the baking from now on.

324
00:19:17,608 --> 00:19:19,318
[CALIFORNIA SIGHS]

325
00:19:19,443 --> 00:19:21,653
So you need to go over
to a store
to see if the sugar is in.

326
00:19:21,779 --> 00:19:24,449
[♪]

327
00:19:29,912 --> 00:19:31,662
Mornin’.

328
00:19:31,747 --> 00:19:33,997
Young lady!

329
00:19:34,124 --> 00:19:36,374
I’m lookin’ for the town
of Lucky Diggins.

330
00:19:36,502 --> 00:19:37,752
Well, this is it.

331
00:19:37,837 --> 00:19:41,507
For the love
of Uncle Peter’s dirty socks,
this is it?

332
00:19:41,590 --> 00:19:43,390
This is all there is.

333
00:19:45,052 --> 00:19:47,922
Hoo! My goodness.

334
00:19:48,013 --> 00:19:50,723
Oh, top of the mornin’
to you, ma’am,

335
00:19:50,850 --> 00:19:54,900
and I can’t remember
the last time I’ve seen such
a fine top of the mornin’.

336
00:19:55,020 --> 00:19:56,190
My name is Brother Claymore.

337
00:19:56,313 --> 00:19:58,393
I am the sole founder
and minister

338
00:19:58,524 --> 00:20:01,154
of the Free and Independent
Church of the Outdoors.

339
00:20:01,235 --> 00:20:03,865
Come here to save souls.

340
00:20:03,946 --> 00:20:08,536
And I was wonderin’
if there’s about here

341
00:20:08,659 --> 00:20:12,669
a family that might
show the charity to possibly
put me up for a spell.

342
00:20:12,746 --> 00:20:15,166
May I be able to depend
on your charity?
You are Sister...

343
00:20:15,249 --> 00:20:17,919
I am Sister nobody,
Mr. Claymore.

344
00:20:18,043 --> 00:20:21,753
I am Arvella Whipple,
and I have little affection
for men of the cloth.

345
00:20:21,881 --> 00:20:24,261
My charity costs
$18.20 a week.

346
00:20:24,383 --> 00:20:25,383
Mama!

347
00:20:29,847 --> 00:20:30,887
[WHISPERING]

348
00:20:31,015 --> 00:20:32,645
[MULE BRAYING]

349
00:20:34,351 --> 00:20:36,221
I’m afraid that we don’t have
that sum, ma’am.

350
00:20:36,353 --> 00:20:39,523
Well, then, the ground
will have to serve you, sir.

351
00:20:39,607 --> 00:20:41,237
Mama, why were you so rude
to that man?

352
00:20:41,317 --> 00:20:43,197
I have no use
for religious men.

353
00:20:43,277 --> 00:20:46,407
They leave a bad taste
in my mouth,
like old mushrooms.

354
00:20:46,530 --> 00:20:49,910
Our pastor back home
knew our family for 50 years,

355
00:20:50,034 --> 00:20:53,164
but when your father died,
because he wasn’t
a churchgoing man,

356
00:20:53,245 --> 00:20:55,375
he refused to bury him.

357
00:20:55,456 --> 00:20:58,376
So thank you just the same.

358
00:21:03,255 --> 00:21:07,255
Now, big old Brother Claymore,
I mean, no one cares a lick
about his sermonizin’.

359
00:21:07,384 --> 00:21:09,264
We’re up there workin’,
he gets up on the rocks

360
00:21:09,386 --> 00:21:11,016
and starts preachin’
to the air.

361
00:21:11,096 --> 00:21:12,846
He sounds like a damn foghorn.

362
00:21:12,932 --> 00:21:15,552
I told him he’d do
a lot better if he worked
as hard at minin’.

363
00:21:15,643 --> 00:21:18,183
Clyde, he laughed.
He said,
"I am minin’, brother.

364
00:21:18,270 --> 00:21:20,110
ALL: "Minin’ for souls."

365
00:21:20,189 --> 00:21:21,819
[ALL LAUGHING]
McPHEE: I listen to him.

366
00:21:21,941 --> 00:21:24,861
It wouldn’t hurt
if some of the rest of you
did too.

367
00:21:24,944 --> 00:21:27,234
Plenty of sinners
at this table.

368
00:21:27,321 --> 00:21:30,201
Damn Bible whacker!
MAN: McPhee!

369
00:21:30,282 --> 00:21:32,282
Sit down
and put that knife away
right now.

370
00:21:32,409 --> 00:21:35,459
I will not tolerate fighting
in this establishment.

371
00:21:42,795 --> 00:21:45,545
Here is the balance
of your bed and board.

372
00:21:45,631 --> 00:21:48,801
Now take it and get out
and don’t come back.

373
00:21:53,097 --> 00:21:54,727
[GROWLING]

374
00:22:03,148 --> 00:22:06,488
Miners don’t have souls
worth saving.

375
00:22:06,610 --> 00:22:09,240
Well, listen to her, will you?
I was gonna propose.

376
00:22:09,321 --> 00:22:12,611
I was gonna make you
Mrs. Amos Frogge
one of these years,

377
00:22:12,700 --> 00:22:14,160
but I don’t know now.

378
00:22:14,284 --> 00:22:16,704
California Frogge. Hmm.
Might be a problem.

379
00:22:16,829 --> 00:22:19,879
People might think
you’re gonna hop, croak
and eat bugs.

380
00:22:19,999 --> 00:22:21,379
[ALL LAUGHING]

381
00:22:21,500 --> 00:22:24,720
AMOS: I can see her now,
jumpin’. The toad girl.

382
00:22:29,174 --> 00:22:31,964
Eatin’ bugs.
That’s a sight. Eatin’ bugs.

383
00:22:32,052 --> 00:22:33,512
Why didn’t you
stand up for me?

384
00:22:33,595 --> 00:22:35,515
I wasn’t the one who told them
they had no souls.

385
00:22:35,597 --> 00:22:37,897
Why do you listen
to those miners, anyway?

386
00:22:38,017 --> 00:22:40,727
Truth is,
you need thicker skin,
California Whipple.

387
00:22:40,853 --> 00:22:42,683
My sister, the swamp frog.

388
00:22:42,813 --> 00:22:44,523
Shut up.

389
00:22:44,606 --> 00:22:47,356
The truth is, you like
having them laugh at me.

390
00:22:47,484 --> 00:22:50,654
At least Pa loved me.
You don’t even like me.

391
00:22:57,953 --> 00:23:00,123
[FIDDLE PLAYING ROMANTIC TUNE]

392
00:23:00,205 --> 00:23:01,745
[ALL CHATTERING]

393
00:23:51,590 --> 00:23:54,140
AMOS: You make this pie,
honeydew?

394
00:23:54,259 --> 00:23:55,429
Yeah.
I changed my mind.

395
00:23:55,552 --> 00:23:57,132
I will marry you
when you grow up.

396
00:23:57,262 --> 00:23:59,592
Mmm! Scrum delicious!

397
00:23:59,681 --> 00:24:01,591
There are gravel monkeys
up in them canyons

398
00:24:01,725 --> 00:24:03,805
livin’ on hog fat
and acorn flour biscuits,

399
00:24:03,936 --> 00:24:06,566
give an ounce of gold
for one of your pies.

400
00:24:06,647 --> 00:24:08,277
ALL: Yeah!

401
00:24:08,357 --> 00:24:09,857
[ALL CLAMORING]

402
00:24:11,985 --> 00:24:15,905
CLYDE: God gives it,
and he gives it to you free.

403
00:24:15,989 --> 00:24:19,579
All that he asks back
is that you love him.

404
00:24:19,660 --> 00:24:22,460
You’re lookin’
in the wrong place, gentlemen.

405
00:24:22,579 --> 00:24:24,669
The gold you seek
is in your own souls.

406
00:24:24,790 --> 00:24:28,880
[CLYDE CONTINUES PREACHING]
Hi! Fresh pies!

407
00:24:28,961 --> 00:24:31,301
Want a pie?
I’ll take one.

408
00:24:31,380 --> 00:24:32,380
One dollar.

409
00:24:32,464 --> 00:24:33,964
One dollar?
Uh‐huh.

410
00:24:35,259 --> 00:24:38,099
Thank you.
Thank you.

411
00:24:38,178 --> 00:24:42,728
Pies! Fruit pies!
You want a pie?

412
00:24:42,808 --> 00:24:45,808
Want a pie?

413
00:24:45,894 --> 00:24:46,894
Pie?

414
00:24:48,147 --> 00:24:49,487
You want a pie?
Nah.

415
00:24:51,191 --> 00:24:52,851
Pies! Fresh pies!

416
00:24:52,985 --> 00:24:55,155
Go on and get out of here.

417
00:24:55,237 --> 00:24:56,197
Go along.

418
00:24:56,321 --> 00:24:57,521
Hey!

419
00:24:58,866 --> 00:25:01,496
He said, "You wanna hide God
from man?

420
00:25:01,618 --> 00:25:05,828
"You really wanna hide him?
You hide God inside man,

421
00:25:05,956 --> 00:25:08,956
"’cause he’ll never think
to look there."

422
00:25:11,211 --> 00:25:13,001
I’m sorry
my mama was rude before.

423
00:25:13,130 --> 00:25:15,300
Oh, that’s all right.

424
00:25:17,384 --> 00:25:19,344
Do ministers speak for God?

425
00:25:19,428 --> 00:25:21,678
No. No man can speak
for God.

426
00:25:21,763 --> 00:25:24,683
But I do know
sometimes God speaks
through men.

427
00:25:24,808 --> 00:25:27,518
You see, I gave God
the reins to my burrow
a long time ago.

428
00:25:27,603 --> 00:25:29,853
I just let him do the drivin’,
because every time I drive it,

429
00:25:29,980 --> 00:25:33,280
somehow or another
I manage to run it
right into the crick.

430
00:25:33,358 --> 00:25:36,198
But I do know that God
will show you the path.

431
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:40,410
And whether or not
you choose it,
now, that’ll be up to you.

432
00:25:44,286 --> 00:25:46,916
What I need is a new name.

433
00:25:47,039 --> 00:25:48,209
Rebecca?

434
00:25:48,290 --> 00:25:49,880
No.

435
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:51,300
Louisa?

436
00:25:51,376 --> 00:25:53,876
Nah, too girlish.

437
00:25:54,004 --> 00:25:55,624
Desdemona?

438
00:25:55,714 --> 00:25:57,294
Ugh.

439
00:25:57,382 --> 00:25:59,172
Lucy?

440
00:25:59,259 --> 00:26:02,979
No. But it’s short.

441
00:26:04,306 --> 00:26:08,686
Lucy. Lucy Whipple.

442
00:26:08,769 --> 00:26:12,739
I’m very pleased to meet you.
My name is Lucy Whipple.

443
00:26:12,814 --> 00:26:18,114
From this day forward,
I will be known to the world
as Lucy Whipple.

444
00:26:19,238 --> 00:26:22,908
Lucy. I like that.

445
00:26:25,285 --> 00:26:26,995
I know 48 words for liquor.

446
00:26:27,079 --> 00:26:29,249
Hooch, cactus juice,
catgut, cougar’s milk,

447
00:26:29,373 --> 00:26:32,873
gator sweat, jack‐a‐dandy,
gullet wash, panther piss,
cough and varnish...

448
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:35,420
Now, why call liquor
cough and varnish?

449
00:26:35,504 --> 00:26:37,334
You’re so dumb, California.

450
00:26:37,422 --> 00:26:41,712
Do you know what’s dumber,
is memorizing stupid words
for liquor.

451
00:26:41,802 --> 00:26:44,552
And I’m not
California anymore.
You can call me Lucy.

452
00:26:44,638 --> 00:26:46,888
What?
I changed my name.

453
00:26:46,974 --> 00:26:49,474
To Lucy?
It sounds like some showoff
from the city.

454
00:26:49,601 --> 00:26:50,851
Ugh and puke.

455
00:26:50,936 --> 00:26:54,396
Shut up, Butte.
You know, Prairie liked it.

456
00:26:54,481 --> 00:26:56,601
Just don’t tell Mama.

457
00:26:56,733 --> 00:26:59,563
Then why did you change
your name?

458
00:27:00,946 --> 00:27:02,486
You wouldn’t understand.

459
00:27:03,448 --> 00:27:04,658
[SCOFFING]

460
00:27:07,452 --> 00:27:13,122
L‐U‐C...

461
00:27:13,208 --> 00:27:15,628
Y.

462
00:27:15,711 --> 00:27:19,051
Good.
Now, what does that spell?

463
00:27:19,131 --> 00:27:20,801
"Lukey."

464
00:27:20,882 --> 00:27:25,462
Close. It’s Lucy.
I’ve changed my name.
I’m Lucy now.

465
00:27:25,595 --> 00:27:29,305
Go to California
and be called California!

466
00:27:29,391 --> 00:27:31,861
Lucy.

467
00:27:31,977 --> 00:27:34,397
L, Y.

468
00:27:34,479 --> 00:27:37,029
Is your pa a miner?

469
00:27:37,149 --> 00:27:38,649
No, miners are bad people.

470
00:27:38,734 --> 00:27:41,484
Well, they do swear
and smell.

471
00:27:41,570 --> 00:27:44,120
And they kill all the Indians.

472
00:27:45,741 --> 00:27:48,041
A...
Where does
the rest of your family live?

473
00:27:50,495 --> 00:27:52,325
Not supposed to tell.

474
00:27:52,456 --> 00:27:53,996
[MAN WHISTLING]

475
00:27:54,124 --> 00:27:56,504
Oh, that’s Joe.

476
00:27:56,626 --> 00:27:58,126
Mornin’ to you, Miss...

477
00:27:59,171 --> 00:28:02,551
Joe, this is Lucy.

478
00:28:02,674 --> 00:28:04,424
Uh, I didn’t know
you had company.

479
00:28:04,509 --> 00:28:06,309
It’s all right.

480
00:28:06,386 --> 00:28:08,096
Pleased to meet you,
Miss Lucy.

481
00:28:08,180 --> 00:28:10,310
I just done come by
to visit Miss Annie here.

482
00:28:10,390 --> 00:28:12,730
I’ve never met
an actual Negro before.

483
00:28:12,851 --> 00:28:16,181
I’ve read about them
in <i>Robinson Crusoe,</i> but...

484
00:28:17,522 --> 00:28:19,142
I’ve never seen you in town.

485
00:28:19,232 --> 00:28:21,442
Do you live...
Do you live off the land,
like Annie?

486
00:28:21,526 --> 00:28:26,616
Uh, I don’t have
as fine a house as Miss Annie
done built herself here,

487
00:28:26,698 --> 00:28:29,868
but I manage,
sleepin’ under the stars.

488
00:28:29,951 --> 00:28:32,241
Well, you should stay
in our boarding tent.

489
00:28:32,371 --> 00:28:36,131
I mean, my mama’s
not a very good cook,
but there’s a lot of food.

490
00:28:36,208 --> 00:28:40,168
No, Missus, I...
I just don’t want to cause
that kind of trouble.

491
00:28:45,425 --> 00:28:47,885
Do you want a chokeberry pie?

492
00:28:48,011 --> 00:28:50,221
It’s only a dollar.

493
00:28:50,347 --> 00:28:52,347
Did your ma cook it?

494
00:28:52,432 --> 00:28:54,552
I did.

495
00:28:54,684 --> 00:28:56,224
In that case,
it’s gold well spent.

496
00:28:56,353 --> 00:28:59,143
I love chokeberry pie.

497
00:28:59,231 --> 00:29:01,571
Thank you.

498
00:29:01,650 --> 00:29:03,160
So you don’t think
I made up Joe?

499
00:29:03,235 --> 00:29:06,655
No. Jimmy Whiskers
knows him too.

500
00:29:06,738 --> 00:29:09,448
What kind of trouble
do you think
he was talking about, Mama?

501
00:29:09,574 --> 00:29:16,414
Well, some white folk think
that colored folk aren’t fit
to live with white people.

502
00:29:16,498 --> 00:29:19,458
Well, he shouldn’t
have to stay in the woods
all winter.

503
00:29:19,584 --> 00:29:21,504
Why doesn’t he stay with us?

504
00:29:21,586 --> 00:29:24,006
Well, that’s not a good idea,
California.

505
00:29:24,089 --> 00:29:26,259
Though he could live
in our mule shed

506
00:29:26,383 --> 00:29:29,713
and I could make him
breakfast and supper
for $10 a week,

507
00:29:29,803 --> 00:29:31,673
if he’ll eat it outside.

508
00:29:31,763 --> 00:29:34,433
That’s the best I could do.
The mule shed?

509
00:29:34,516 --> 00:29:37,766
Mama, do you think
he’s not fit to live
with other white people?

510
00:29:37,853 --> 00:29:40,103
Don’t preach to me,
California.

511
00:29:40,230 --> 00:29:41,860
Take it or leave it.

512
00:29:41,940 --> 00:29:44,110
Fine.

513
00:29:44,192 --> 00:29:47,312
I’ve changed my name to Lucy,
by the way.

514
00:29:47,446 --> 00:29:49,526
Take it or leave it.

515
00:29:49,614 --> 00:29:51,824
Come back here.

516
00:29:51,950 --> 00:29:54,460
What do you mean,
you’ve changed your name?

517
00:29:54,536 --> 00:29:57,376
California is a place,
not a person.

518
00:29:57,456 --> 00:30:01,296
What kind of mother
would name her daughter
after a godforsaken state?

519
00:30:01,376 --> 00:30:03,256
It just proves
that you hate me.

520
00:30:03,336 --> 00:30:05,426
Don’t you ever say that again.

521
00:30:05,505 --> 00:30:08,715
If you weren’t so selfish
and stubborn, I would tell you
how I feel about you.

522
00:30:08,800 --> 00:30:11,600
Until then, don’t make
such outlandish assumptions.

523
00:30:20,145 --> 00:30:22,275
My master’s name
was Mr. Sawyer.

524
00:30:22,355 --> 00:30:25,315
He took to drinkin’
by night

525
00:30:25,442 --> 00:30:26,652
and beatin’ me
by day.

526
00:30:26,776 --> 00:30:28,946
So one night when Master Sawyer
was drunk,

527
00:30:29,029 --> 00:30:33,829
I let off.
I took a horse.

528
00:30:33,950 --> 00:30:36,670
Miss Lucy, I know that done
right make me a thief,

529
00:30:36,745 --> 00:30:39,165
but out here,
I ain’t no slave.

530
00:30:39,247 --> 00:30:40,787
I’s free.

531
00:30:40,874 --> 00:30:46,004
I’d just as soon live outside
as in. Thanks for savin’ me.

532
00:30:49,049 --> 00:30:50,599
What’s your last name,
Joe?

533
00:30:50,675 --> 00:30:52,005
Don’t know.

534
00:30:52,135 --> 00:30:53,635
Master called
all his slaves "Joe."

535
00:30:53,720 --> 00:30:55,020
Easy to remember.

536
00:30:55,096 --> 00:30:56,686
Well, everyone should have
their own name,

537
00:30:56,765 --> 00:30:58,555
especially one you like.

538
00:30:58,683 --> 00:31:00,473
I’m an expert
on name changing.

539
00:31:00,560 --> 00:31:02,400
Don’t bother.
It’s okay.

540
00:31:02,521 --> 00:31:05,361
I have the perfect name
for you.

541
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:07,360
Bernard.

542
00:31:07,484 --> 00:31:09,944
It was my father’s name.

543
00:31:10,028 --> 00:31:14,328
He had big hands like you
and he was sweet like you also.

544
00:31:14,407 --> 00:31:15,697
Bernard?

545
00:31:18,245 --> 00:31:19,745
I like it.

546
00:31:19,871 --> 00:31:21,661
It’s a mighty fine name,
Miss Lucy.

547
00:31:21,748 --> 00:31:23,798
I’ll be proud
to carry it.

548
00:31:23,875 --> 00:31:26,665
Well, I’m very pleased
to meet you, Mr. Bernard.

549
00:31:27,671 --> 00:31:31,341
Pleased to meet you too,
Miss Lucy.

550
00:31:31,424 --> 00:31:33,634
Cut it like this.

551
00:31:33,718 --> 00:31:34,928
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

552
00:31:35,053 --> 00:31:36,053
See?

553
00:31:37,764 --> 00:31:40,184
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

554
00:31:40,267 --> 00:31:42,807
Your friend Annie teach you
how to make that?

555
00:31:42,894 --> 00:31:44,394
So you believe me now?

556
00:31:44,479 --> 00:31:47,569
Scatter says
her ma and pa live
up on Bottle Creek.

557
00:31:47,649 --> 00:31:48,899
She has some brothers too.

558
00:31:49,025 --> 00:31:51,065
Well, how come
they don’t come into town?

559
00:31:51,152 --> 00:31:52,272
I don’t know.

560
00:31:52,404 --> 00:31:54,784
But I don’t want you
going up there, ever.

561
00:31:54,906 --> 00:31:56,156
Well, why not?

562
00:31:56,241 --> 00:31:57,871
You can visit with Annie
in the woods,

563
00:31:57,951 --> 00:31:59,791
and she’s welcome
to come here,
but don’t go there.

564
00:31:59,911 --> 00:32:01,491
But you have to have
some kind of reason.

565
00:32:01,580 --> 00:32:04,250
The reason is,
I said don’t go there.

566
00:32:04,332 --> 00:32:07,752
Now go find something
useful to do, goose.
Play’s over.

567
00:32:11,673 --> 00:32:13,133
[LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING]

568
00:32:13,258 --> 00:32:14,428
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

569
00:32:16,803 --> 00:32:18,423
What are they celebrating?

570
00:32:18,555 --> 00:32:20,685
The gents struck it rich.

571
00:32:20,765 --> 00:32:22,145
Gold is awful.

572
00:32:22,267 --> 00:32:24,817
We should have stayed
in Buttonfields.

573
00:32:24,936 --> 00:32:28,276
Pa said it was
a little piece of heaven.

574
00:32:28,398 --> 00:32:29,988
Well, it wasn’t.

575
00:32:30,108 --> 00:32:32,528
Your pa kept you away
from anything unpleasant.

576
00:32:32,611 --> 00:32:35,991
ARVELLA: He really didn’t have
much use for the real world.

577
00:32:36,114 --> 00:32:39,694
Well, why would he think
California would be better?

578
00:32:39,784 --> 00:32:42,784
Why don’t we just
get some sleep?

579
00:32:42,871 --> 00:32:44,081
Good night, Mama.

580
00:32:44,164 --> 00:32:45,874
Why don’t you
ever talk to me, Mama?

581
00:32:45,957 --> 00:32:47,837
If I talked to you
every time you wanted to talk,

582
00:32:47,959 --> 00:32:49,969
nothing would ever get done.
Night, Mama.

583
00:32:50,045 --> 00:32:52,465
Well, we’re not
doing anything now.
We can’t even sleep.

584
00:32:52,547 --> 00:32:55,297
It’s just not the time, Lucy.

585
00:32:58,345 --> 00:32:59,975
You called me Lucy.

586
00:33:09,981 --> 00:33:12,521
I would like to welcome
Mr. Claymore to our table.

587
00:33:12,651 --> 00:33:15,071
Well, that’s kind
of you, Mrs. Whipple.
Thank you.

588
00:33:15,153 --> 00:33:17,323
AMOS: Uh, Clyde,
what is this religion
you’re preachin’?

589
00:33:17,447 --> 00:33:18,867
What are the rules?

590
00:33:18,990 --> 00:33:21,620
Amos, I’m not big on rules.
I preach free will.

591
00:33:21,701 --> 00:33:24,821
Although I have to tell you,
I haven’t had much success
as a preacher.

592
00:33:24,913 --> 00:33:28,293
I’ve had no converts.
I have no followers.

593
00:33:28,375 --> 00:33:31,335
But I do know that there’s
gonna be wagon trains
headin’ back east

594
00:33:31,419 --> 00:33:33,929
full of people who feel that
God does not wanna know them

595
00:33:34,005 --> 00:33:37,345
because they have not acquired
the riches expected of them.

596
00:33:37,425 --> 00:33:40,345
And I think someone
should go along to remind them
that God is with them,

597
00:33:40,428 --> 00:33:44,018
always has been with them,
and always will be with them.

598
00:33:44,140 --> 00:33:46,020
So I’m thinkin’
of goin’ along.

599
00:33:46,142 --> 00:33:48,562
Brother Claymore,
would you refuse
to bury someone

600
00:33:48,687 --> 00:33:50,477
because he wasn’t
a churchgoing man?

601
00:33:50,563 --> 00:33:55,483
Absolutely not.
I say the man doesn’t
need church to know God,

602
00:33:55,568 --> 00:33:58,618
and I can’t see
how not buryin’ a man
would help him, help me,

603
00:33:58,697 --> 00:34:00,197
or especially help God.

604
00:34:00,281 --> 00:34:03,031
AMOS:
That’s a real good point,
Reverend.

605
00:34:05,537 --> 00:34:11,047
No, Lucy, I will not allow you
to trek 3000 miles back east
with Mr. Claymore.

606
00:34:11,126 --> 00:34:13,586
One good answer
does not make a good man.

607
00:34:13,712 --> 00:34:16,792
And one bad pastor
doesn’t make them all bad,
either.

608
00:34:16,881 --> 00:34:18,421
Well, listen to you.

609
00:34:18,550 --> 00:34:22,640
You’re getting mighty good
at standing up to me lately.

610
00:34:22,721 --> 00:34:24,061
[SIGHS]

611
00:34:24,180 --> 00:34:26,100
Someone else
can do the baking.

612
00:34:26,224 --> 00:34:29,054
I don’t need a baker, Lucy.
I can do that myself.

613
00:34:29,144 --> 00:34:31,814
What I need is
to find some way

614
00:34:31,896 --> 00:34:37,236
to pull myself up
out of the void left
by the death of your father.

615
00:34:39,529 --> 00:34:41,239
So please help me.

616
00:34:43,074 --> 00:34:45,154
LUCY:
<i>Dear Gram and Grampop,</i>

617
00:34:45,243 --> 00:34:49,243
<i>please plant bluebells
on Papa’s grave
next time you visit.</i>

618
00:34:49,330 --> 00:34:51,710
<i>They finally built us
a new boardinghouse,</i>

619
00:34:51,791 --> 00:34:55,831
<i>but we still live in a tent
so small you couldn’t
swing a cat by its tail.</i>

620
00:34:55,920 --> 00:34:56,970
Got it!

621
00:34:57,088 --> 00:34:59,338
[ALL CHEERING]

622
00:34:59,424 --> 00:35:01,254
[LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING]

623
00:35:02,927 --> 00:35:04,597
AMOS:
Man, how ’bout a dance?

624
00:35:04,679 --> 00:35:07,139
SNOOSE:
As long as I can lead.

625
00:35:07,265 --> 00:35:09,895
If you are not
a vision of beauty,
Mrs. Whipple.

626
00:35:09,976 --> 00:35:14,226
Well, I wish you wouldn’t
exaggerate, Mr. Claymore,
but thank you kindly.

627
00:35:14,314 --> 00:35:17,274
I just hope
we’re gonna have enough pies
for everyone.

628
00:35:21,821 --> 00:35:25,031
It is rude to stare,
Mr. Claymore.

629
00:35:28,286 --> 00:35:30,206
These are for you, Mama.

630
00:35:30,288 --> 00:35:34,048
Papa used to get bluebells,
but they don’t grow
around here.

631
00:35:34,125 --> 00:35:35,375
May I have this dance?

632
00:35:35,460 --> 00:35:37,130
You most certainly may.

633
00:35:38,797 --> 00:35:40,967
I’ll guard those for you.

634
00:35:41,841 --> 00:35:43,421
Thank you.

635
00:35:43,510 --> 00:35:44,510
MAN: Here we go!

636
00:35:49,557 --> 00:35:53,267
We talked about this, Annie.
I’m gonna be at your side
every minute.

637
00:35:53,353 --> 00:35:56,563
And there’s gonna be food
and dancing and storytelling.

638
00:35:56,648 --> 00:35:58,358
Bernard, tell her.

639
00:35:58,483 --> 00:36:00,773
I’s ain’t so sure I should
go in on my own self,
Miss Lucy.

640
00:36:00,860 --> 00:36:01,820
[SIGHING]

641
00:36:01,945 --> 00:36:04,115
You both are going.

642
00:36:09,202 --> 00:36:12,572
Let’s go, Bernard.
Come on.

643
00:36:15,708 --> 00:36:20,718
Hello. I’m Lucy Whipple.
This is Annie Flagg
and Bernard Freeman.

644
00:36:25,510 --> 00:36:29,390
Mrs. Whipple, I don’t know
why your daughter
brought those two in here,

645
00:36:29,514 --> 00:36:31,014
but they can’t stay.

646
00:36:31,099 --> 00:36:34,359
Really?
Well, I admire her for it,

647
00:36:34,477 --> 00:36:36,777
having the courage
to befriend outcasts.

648
00:36:36,855 --> 00:36:39,235
That’s what Jesus did so well,
isn’t that so, Mr. Claymore?

649
00:36:39,357 --> 00:36:40,777
That is the gospel truth.

650
00:36:40,859 --> 00:36:42,859
And should we do any less,
Mr. Scatter?

651
00:36:42,986 --> 00:36:44,066
Come with me, please.

652
00:36:44,195 --> 00:36:46,195
Mrs. Whipple...

653
00:36:47,740 --> 00:36:52,210
Lucy, Mr. Scatter
has something to say
to your friends.

654
00:36:54,205 --> 00:36:56,415
I just...
Just that I, um...

655
00:36:56,541 --> 00:37:01,221
I, uh...
Welcome to our party.

656
00:37:02,422 --> 00:37:04,632
That’s all.
Welcome aboard.

657
00:37:08,011 --> 00:37:12,441
Annie, Bernard,
this is my mama.

658
00:37:12,557 --> 00:37:13,847
Welcome. Welcome.

659
00:37:13,933 --> 00:37:16,353
Thank you kindly.

660
00:37:22,317 --> 00:37:25,737
This here is the ballad
of Rattlesnake Jake,

661
00:37:25,862 --> 00:37:28,112
a man with a devil’s grin.

662
00:37:28,239 --> 00:37:30,409
He’d pick his teeth
with a bowie knife,

663
00:37:30,533 --> 00:37:33,993
and he’d rob, and he’d shoot,
and he’d kill.

664
00:37:34,078 --> 00:37:39,208
Then Sheriff Ben Bueller,
he came to town
with a star of shiny tin.

665
00:37:39,292 --> 00:37:43,082
And he said, "I swear
upon my mother’s grave

666
00:37:43,171 --> 00:37:45,591
"I’m gonna bring
that bastard in."

667
00:37:45,673 --> 00:37:49,173
Now, Sheriff Ben Bueller,
he drew first,

668
00:37:49,260 --> 00:37:51,140
but a gunfighter he was not.

669
00:37:51,262 --> 00:37:55,092
But Jake was ready,
he was cool as ice,

670
00:37:55,224 --> 00:37:58,934
and he dropped him
with just one shot.

671
00:37:59,062 --> 00:38:02,932
Now, the bullet went
through the Sheriff’s skull
like piercin’ an empty can,

672
00:38:03,024 --> 00:38:06,604
bounced off a bedpost
made of iron
and off a miner’s pickin’ pan.

673
00:38:06,694 --> 00:38:08,904
And out through the window
that bullet flew,

674
00:38:08,988 --> 00:38:10,988
like a projectile
surely beguiled,

675
00:38:11,115 --> 00:38:13,705
and it pierced the heart
of a grizzly bear

676
00:38:13,785 --> 00:38:17,745
about to devour a child.

677
00:38:20,083 --> 00:38:22,953
Now, when the posse
caught up to Jake,

678
00:38:23,044 --> 00:38:24,794
he actually shed a tear.

679
00:38:24,879 --> 00:38:29,969
[IN HUSKY VOICE] Said,
"I’m sorry that Sheriff,
he got in the way.

680
00:38:30,093 --> 00:38:33,633
"I was just aimin’
at a hungry bear."

681
00:38:33,721 --> 00:38:35,591
Thunderation,
that man’s a vicious liar!

682
00:38:35,682 --> 00:38:37,302
Oh, shush, shush.
If I catch up with him...

683
00:38:37,433 --> 00:38:42,973
So Jake went free
to rob and kill and maim

684
00:38:43,106 --> 00:38:45,026
with no remorse.

685
00:38:45,149 --> 00:38:48,779
And he picked his teeth
with his bowie knife

686
00:38:48,861 --> 00:38:52,531
as he rode off on his horse.

687
00:38:52,657 --> 00:38:59,167
So if, in your camp,
you should spy a man
whose smile is fake,

688
00:38:59,288 --> 00:39:03,208
lock up your gold,
your wife and your dog,

689
00:39:03,334 --> 00:39:08,374
’cause it might be
Rattlesnake Jake.

690
00:39:08,506 --> 00:39:12,386
Damnation!
Amos, you got us all riled up.

691
00:39:12,510 --> 00:39:14,970
Mr. Scatter,
can you open the bar?

692
00:39:15,054 --> 00:39:16,224
The saloon is open!

693
00:39:16,347 --> 00:39:17,887
[ALL CHEERING]

694
00:39:23,688 --> 00:39:25,818
AMOS: Quite a little tale,
right, Brother?

695
00:39:25,898 --> 00:39:27,988
It’s a fine story.
Thank you.

696
00:39:28,067 --> 00:39:30,197
That’s a fine, fine story.
Thank you.

697
00:39:30,319 --> 00:39:31,489
That was terrifying.

698
00:39:31,571 --> 00:39:32,951
Truth makes
the most powerful story.

699
00:39:33,031 --> 00:39:34,491
CLYDE: But you tell it good.

700
00:39:48,379 --> 00:39:53,469
Might you mind joinin’ me
in a celebratory potation?

701
00:39:55,553 --> 00:39:58,683
I thank you kindly,
Mr. Claymore,
but I don’t drink.

702
00:40:00,224 --> 00:40:01,894
Well, actually, neither do I.

703
00:40:01,976 --> 00:40:03,226
[CHUCKLES]

704
00:40:09,567 --> 00:40:10,907
Good night, Mrs. Whipple.

705
00:40:10,985 --> 00:40:12,235
Arvella.

706
00:40:13,112 --> 00:40:14,232
Excuse me?

707
00:40:14,363 --> 00:40:16,943
My Christian name is Arvella.

708
00:40:18,951 --> 00:40:21,161
Well, good night, Arvella.

709
00:40:21,245 --> 00:40:22,825
Good night.

710
00:40:34,008 --> 00:40:35,678
It’s Buck McPhee.
It has to be.

711
00:40:35,760 --> 00:40:37,140
No one is his friend,

712
00:40:37,261 --> 00:40:40,381
and he doesn’t let anyone
in his tent.

713
00:40:40,473 --> 00:40:43,973
And he has
that huge bowie knife.

714
00:40:44,102 --> 00:40:45,472
He has to be Rattlesnake Jake.

715
00:40:45,603 --> 00:40:48,223
But I thought
it was only a tall tale.

716
00:40:48,314 --> 00:40:50,104
But Buck is different.

717
00:40:50,233 --> 00:40:55,023
He has snake eyes
and he doesn’t drink
or swear like everyone else.

718
00:40:55,113 --> 00:40:56,443
Why?

719
00:40:56,531 --> 00:40:58,661
But Jake could
do those things, California.

720
00:40:58,783 --> 00:41:00,193
Lucy.

721
00:41:00,284 --> 00:41:03,664
But not if he’s trying
to conceal his identity.

722
00:41:03,788 --> 00:41:07,588
And if he were
Rattlesnake Jake,

723
00:41:07,667 --> 00:41:10,877
I’m sure
there’s some kind of reward
for his capture.

724
00:41:10,962 --> 00:41:15,422
And if I got that reward,
I’d have enough money
to go back home.

725
00:41:23,057 --> 00:41:25,147
[HORSE NEIGHING]

726
00:41:25,226 --> 00:41:28,146
There he is.

727
00:41:28,229 --> 00:41:29,779
He comes this far
every Sunday.

728
00:41:29,856 --> 00:41:31,316
Are you sure he be Jake?

729
00:41:31,440 --> 00:41:33,780
"Is," not "be."
He is Jake.

730
00:41:33,860 --> 00:41:37,280
Maybe this is where
he buries his victims.

731
00:41:38,364 --> 00:41:39,734
There he is.

732
00:41:41,159 --> 00:41:42,499
See that bag on the side
of his saddle?

733
00:41:42,618 --> 00:41:45,628
There’s probably
a head in there.

734
00:41:45,705 --> 00:41:47,915
Come on.
Let’s get down there.

735
00:41:58,676 --> 00:42:01,966
I believe he’s takin’
a bath, Lucy.

736
00:42:02,054 --> 00:42:05,514
I suppose
even Rattlesnake Jake
takes a bath.

737
00:42:07,852 --> 00:42:09,352
Don’t look.

738
00:42:09,478 --> 00:42:12,818
Why? We can look.

739
00:42:12,899 --> 00:42:15,529
Don’t matter.

740
00:42:21,073 --> 00:42:24,703
I believe he’s a she.

741
00:42:29,040 --> 00:42:30,840
Oh, come on!

742
00:42:34,795 --> 00:42:36,715
LUCY:
<i>Dear Gram and Grampop,</i>

743
00:42:36,839 --> 00:42:39,549
<i>Lucky Diggins
is a very strange place.</i>

744
00:42:39,634 --> 00:42:42,384
<i>Nothing is ever
what it seems, ever.</i>

745
00:42:42,470 --> 00:42:44,390
<i>Butte’s caught the gold bug.</i>

746
00:42:44,513 --> 00:42:48,893
<i>He quit his job at
Scatter’s Store and is panning
</i> <i>at Cyclone Creek.</i>

747
00:42:48,976 --> 00:42:53,436
<i>He’s crazy.
All miners are crazy.</i>

748
00:42:53,564 --> 00:42:56,564
<i>I’ve started a lending library
at 5 cents a book.</i>

749
00:42:56,692 --> 00:43:01,572
<i>What’s so surprising
is that miners want books.</i>

750
00:43:01,656 --> 00:43:04,746
<i>I miss Gram’s
Indian pudding with cream</i>

751
00:43:04,825 --> 00:43:09,375
<i>and Grampop’s laugh
like a locomotive starting up.</i>

752
00:43:09,455 --> 00:43:13,245
<i>I wish I could come home
to live with you both.</i>

753
00:43:13,334 --> 00:43:16,624
<i>Your granddaughter, Lucy.</i>

754
00:43:16,754 --> 00:43:19,964
<i>P. S. I’ve changed my name
to Lucy.</i>

755
00:43:20,091 --> 00:43:22,101
<i>California is dead.</i>

756
00:43:23,970 --> 00:43:25,430
[BUTTE EXCLAIMING]

757
00:43:28,182 --> 00:43:29,932
What’s wrong, Mama?

758
00:43:40,278 --> 00:43:41,868
You stay here.

759
00:43:47,451 --> 00:43:48,651
What the...?

760
00:43:49,620 --> 00:43:52,000
There’s somebody
in the water!

761
00:43:52,123 --> 00:43:53,123
The boy’s in the water.

762
00:43:53,207 --> 00:43:54,497
Get him, Amos.
I can’t swim.

763
00:43:54,625 --> 00:43:57,255
I can’t either.
Somebody’s in the water!

764
00:43:57,336 --> 00:43:59,506
Boy in the water!
Boy in the water!

765
00:43:59,630 --> 00:44:02,470
Rusty, get him
from your side!

766
00:44:02,550 --> 00:44:05,010
Get him!
Boy in the water!

767
00:44:09,140 --> 00:44:11,060
We gotta help him.

768
00:44:12,476 --> 00:44:15,016
I got you. Hold on.

769
00:44:15,146 --> 00:44:17,106
I’ll get to you, Clyde!

770
00:44:22,486 --> 00:44:26,196
Clyde, grab this!

771
00:44:26,324 --> 00:44:28,824
Hold on! Hold on!

772
00:44:30,161 --> 00:44:31,171
AMOS: Got you!

773
00:44:31,287 --> 00:44:33,667
Boys, boys, pull him out.

774
00:44:33,789 --> 00:44:35,839
Take my hand.
Pull him out.

775
00:44:39,462 --> 00:44:41,082
Give me the boy.

776
00:44:49,347 --> 00:44:51,687
Don’t you let that life
out of you, son.

777
00:44:51,766 --> 00:44:53,436
CLYDE: Don’t give up, son.
Don’t give up.

778
00:44:53,517 --> 00:44:54,807
Here comes his ma.

779
00:44:54,894 --> 00:44:55,854
Hold on, son!

780
00:44:55,936 --> 00:44:57,356
CLYDE: Son.
[WAILING] Oh, no!

781
00:44:57,438 --> 00:44:58,648
Don’t die, boy.

782
00:44:59,648 --> 00:45:01,858
You hold on
to that life, boy.

783
00:45:03,486 --> 00:45:05,866
Boy, don’t die. Stay with me.

784
00:45:05,946 --> 00:45:08,616
Don’t you let that life
out of you, son.

785
00:45:08,699 --> 00:45:11,209
Come back here, boy.

786
00:45:11,327 --> 00:45:13,537
[ARVELLA CRYING]
Hold on.

787
00:45:13,621 --> 00:45:16,251
Stay with me, son.
Stay with me, boy.

788
00:45:16,374 --> 00:45:17,914
[GRUNTING]

789
00:45:18,042 --> 00:45:19,582
[COUGHING]

790
00:45:25,424 --> 00:45:27,594
[COUGHING]

791
00:45:27,718 --> 00:45:30,678
ARVELLA: Is he all right?
Is he all right?

792
00:45:32,390 --> 00:45:35,860
Thank you, Mr. Claymore.

793
00:45:35,935 --> 00:45:39,725
You better thank God,
Mrs. Whipple,
’cause I can’t swim.

794
00:45:49,198 --> 00:45:50,748
[CRYING] My baby.

795
00:45:52,827 --> 00:45:54,167
[COUGHING]
LUCY: <i>Dear Gram and Grampop,</i>

796
00:45:54,245 --> 00:45:55,915
<i>Mr. Scatter says
Butte swallowed water</i>

797
00:45:55,996 --> 00:45:59,086
<i>that’s been poisoned
by mining.</i>

798
00:45:59,166 --> 00:46:01,666
<i>But I’ve seen raccoons
drinking from it
every morning,</i>

799
00:46:01,752 --> 00:46:03,792
<i>and they’re fine.</i>

800
00:46:03,921 --> 00:46:06,501
[COUGHING]
Take another. Take another.

801
00:46:06,590 --> 00:46:07,850
[MOANING]

802
00:46:07,925 --> 00:46:09,215
Good boy.

803
00:46:09,301 --> 00:46:11,091
[GASPING]
Okay.

804
00:46:11,178 --> 00:46:12,268
[COUGHING]

805
00:46:12,346 --> 00:46:14,386
Good boy. Shh.

806
00:46:14,473 --> 00:46:17,603
[SHUSHING]

807
00:46:17,685 --> 00:46:19,185
Aren’t there any doctors
close by?

808
00:46:19,270 --> 00:46:20,780
There’s no work for ’em.

809
00:46:20,855 --> 00:46:23,565
A miner would rather die
than give a doctor his gold.

810
00:46:23,649 --> 00:46:28,029
Maybe Sacramento,
but that’s four days
by riverboat.

811
00:46:28,112 --> 00:46:29,692
It’d be a whole lot faster
by horse.

812
00:46:29,780 --> 00:46:31,620
I got a good horse.

813
00:46:33,033 --> 00:46:35,613
I’ll go, Lucy.

814
00:46:39,707 --> 00:46:41,627
[CHUCKLING]
Amos got it wrong.

815
00:46:41,750 --> 00:46:44,170
The bullet stuck
right in the Sheriff’s hat.

816
00:46:44,295 --> 00:46:46,125
It was hard as a rock.

817
00:46:46,255 --> 00:46:47,295
Murder, it was.

818
00:46:47,381 --> 00:46:48,631
[GRUNTS]

819
00:46:50,801 --> 00:46:53,421
[IN WOMAN’S VOICE]
Just kiddin’, Lucy.

820
00:46:53,512 --> 00:46:55,762
Listen,

821
00:46:55,848 --> 00:46:58,558
don’t tell anyone
my secret, okay?

822
00:46:58,642 --> 00:47:00,302
I like gold,

823
00:47:01,645 --> 00:47:04,315
but I don’t trust miners
with women.

824
00:47:07,651 --> 00:47:08,941
Hyah!

825
00:47:09,987 --> 00:47:12,027
Watch it!

826
00:47:12,156 --> 00:47:13,996
Dag diddy.

827
00:47:14,074 --> 00:47:15,194
[SIGHS]

828
00:47:15,326 --> 00:47:16,956
Dag diddy!

829
00:47:18,704 --> 00:47:21,084
Buck went for the doctor?

830
00:47:21,165 --> 00:47:24,295
Buck is not
Rattlesnake Jake, Butte.
I told you that.

831
00:47:24,376 --> 00:47:27,336
The good news
is she’ll be back
in two days.

832
00:47:27,463 --> 00:47:29,673
The doctor’s a woman?

833
00:47:29,798 --> 00:47:33,928
No, um, Buck’s horse is.
She’s a mare.

834
00:47:39,266 --> 00:47:44,566
If I die, you won’t have
a man in the family.

835
00:47:44,688 --> 00:47:46,818
We don’t have one now, Butte.

836
00:47:46,899 --> 00:47:50,359
But, if by some impossible,

837
00:47:50,444 --> 00:47:54,944
one‐in‐a‐billion chance
something happens to you,

838
00:47:55,032 --> 00:47:57,952
me and Mama can take care
of the family just fine.

839
00:47:59,787 --> 00:48:02,627
I guess you could.

840
00:48:02,706 --> 00:48:06,256
You have a lot of guts
after all, Lucy.

841
00:48:11,549 --> 00:48:13,389
I remembered some more.

842
00:48:15,302 --> 00:48:18,922
Bug juice, chain lightning

843
00:48:20,724 --> 00:48:22,224
and sheep wash.

844
00:48:24,103 --> 00:48:26,143
[♪]

845
00:48:38,576 --> 00:48:40,156
If Butte dies,

846
00:48:41,912 --> 00:48:44,082
I’ll never talk again.

847
00:48:47,543 --> 00:48:50,663
My sister, she died.

848
00:48:50,754 --> 00:48:52,464
She was 6.

849
00:48:54,258 --> 00:48:56,888
What happened to her?

850
00:48:56,969 --> 00:49:01,059
I talk to her a lot
and she talks back,
so I don’t miss her.

851
00:49:03,142 --> 00:49:06,262
But you can’t talk
to a dead person, Annie.

852
00:49:07,855 --> 00:49:10,275
You know words
and writin’,

853
00:49:11,275 --> 00:49:13,945
but some things
you don’t know.

854
00:49:21,910 --> 00:49:25,460
I was...
I was blowing my whistle
in my dream.

855
00:49:27,166 --> 00:49:30,376
Do you think I’ll have it
where I’m going, Mama?

856
00:49:36,050 --> 00:49:38,430
I wish I got to be a man.

857
00:49:40,012 --> 00:49:42,512
I saw the elephant,
didn’t I?

858
00:49:45,851 --> 00:49:50,681
I feel
like all the kick’s
drifting out of me.

859
00:49:50,814 --> 00:49:51,984
[GASPING]

860
00:49:52,066 --> 00:49:56,486
Like steam
rising from wet shoes.

861
00:49:56,570 --> 00:49:58,330
[INAUDIBLE]

862
00:50:00,574 --> 00:50:01,994
Phlegm cutter

863
00:50:05,204 --> 00:50:09,374
is the 49th word
for liquor.

864
00:50:12,586 --> 00:50:14,176
[EXHALING HEAVILY]

865
00:50:27,851 --> 00:50:29,471
[MOANING]

866
00:50:44,284 --> 00:50:46,164
[ARVELLA SOBBING]

867
00:50:54,586 --> 00:50:56,256
[CRYING]

868
00:51:02,469 --> 00:51:04,559
I’ll prepare his body.

869
00:51:21,947 --> 00:51:24,157
I got the doctor.

870
00:51:24,241 --> 00:51:25,571
It’s too late.

871
00:51:45,721 --> 00:51:50,441
Please, let’s not
dishonor Butte Whipple
by mournin’ his passing.

872
00:51:52,019 --> 00:51:53,859
But let’s rather
celebrate his presence

873
00:51:53,937 --> 00:51:57,737
and the fact that
God honored us with him.

874
00:51:57,816 --> 00:52:00,736
All that’s happened here now
is that God’s called him home.

875
00:52:00,819 --> 00:52:02,279
[SOBBING]

876
00:52:36,939 --> 00:52:40,989
Heaven’s brew.
That’s the 50th.

877
00:52:42,611 --> 00:52:44,991
[♪]

878
00:53:04,591 --> 00:53:08,711
He was looking for gold
so I wouldn’t have to work
so hard.

879
00:53:11,014 --> 00:53:13,594
Sure is a noble gesture,
isn’t it?

880
00:53:15,018 --> 00:53:18,028
Noble for anyone,
let alone a 10‐year‐old.

881
00:53:27,281 --> 00:53:31,541
Made nobler by the fact
that you never asked him
to do it.

882
00:53:31,660 --> 00:53:33,500
[SOBBING]

883
00:53:37,207 --> 00:53:39,457
It’s all right.

884
00:53:39,543 --> 00:53:40,703
It’s all right.

885
00:53:43,589 --> 00:53:46,389
She hasn’t talked
or hardly eaten in days.
I just...

886
00:53:46,466 --> 00:53:48,056
You’re gettin’
the boarders fed.

887
00:53:48,135 --> 00:53:50,765
[SIGHING]
I don’t know what to do.

888
00:53:50,888 --> 00:53:52,888
This is what you can do.

889
00:53:53,015 --> 00:53:55,225
She’ll come back
when she’s ready.

890
00:54:06,486 --> 00:54:09,486
Here, Mama,
I made this for you to try.

891
00:54:10,741 --> 00:54:12,581
Here.
No, thank you.

892
00:54:32,429 --> 00:54:33,639
Arvella,

893
00:54:39,353 --> 00:54:42,683
you can sit out here
until the cows come home,

894
00:54:42,773 --> 00:54:45,603
but that’s not gonna
bring your Butte back.

895
00:54:47,569 --> 00:54:50,529
You know,
you have to let him live
in your heart.

896
00:54:50,614 --> 00:54:53,404
’Cause he’s no further
than your heart.

897
00:54:55,702 --> 00:54:58,992
But you have to start tendin’
to your daughter,

898
00:54:59,122 --> 00:55:03,292
or else I know that
you’ll surely lose her.

899
00:55:03,377 --> 00:55:07,297
Well, maybe
not in body,

900
00:55:07,381 --> 00:55:10,391
but in soul, and that’s
much more important.

901
00:55:26,149 --> 00:55:28,239
[CRYING]

902
00:55:42,290 --> 00:55:44,170
I’m sorry, Lucy.

903
00:55:45,794 --> 00:55:47,464
I’m so sorry.

904
00:55:50,507 --> 00:55:53,427
I did wrong
to drag you children
to this wild place.

905
00:55:53,510 --> 00:55:54,680
Mama, don’t.

906
00:55:56,263 --> 00:55:59,843
I keep thinking that Butte
would still be alive

907
00:55:59,975 --> 00:56:01,805
if I hadn’t insisted that...

908
00:56:01,893 --> 00:56:03,353
It’s not your fault.

909
00:56:03,437 --> 00:56:05,817
People die everywhere.

910
00:56:05,897 --> 00:56:08,777
Pa died in Massachusetts.

911
00:56:08,859 --> 00:56:10,859
It’s not your fault, Mama.

912
00:56:13,155 --> 00:56:15,945
You and I are so different.

913
00:56:16,033 --> 00:56:18,573
Me always looking ahead,

914
00:56:18,702 --> 00:56:23,372
you always looking behind
at what you loved and lost.

915
00:56:24,499 --> 00:56:26,879
I just wanted us to be safe.

916
00:56:28,336 --> 00:56:30,546
There’s no place that’s safe.

917
00:56:32,424 --> 00:56:35,174
Just God’s abiding love
and our own two feet.

918
00:56:35,260 --> 00:56:37,390
We have to trust in both.

919
00:56:40,474 --> 00:56:42,934
Butte trusted, and he’s dead.

920
00:56:44,478 --> 00:56:49,398
And when you see God,
you can ask him why.

921
00:57:08,835 --> 00:57:11,215
Butte’s paying us a visit.

922
00:57:14,549 --> 00:57:15,679
Yeah.

923
00:57:29,231 --> 00:57:32,071
LUCY: <i>Dear Gram and Grampop,</i>

924
00:57:32,150 --> 00:57:34,110
<i>Butte is dead.</i>

925
00:57:34,194 --> 00:57:38,614
<i>And now that he’s gone,
I realize how much
I truly loved him.</i>

926
00:57:38,698 --> 00:57:43,368
<i>He was my friend,
and now I need a friend
more than ever.</i>

927
00:57:48,375 --> 00:57:50,875
Annie? Annie!

928
00:57:57,634 --> 00:57:58,804
[GROWLING]

929
00:58:28,540 --> 00:58:30,340
What happened to you?

930
00:58:30,458 --> 00:58:31,958
LINUS: Who is it?
Go away, Lucy.

931
00:58:32,043 --> 00:58:34,083
LINUS: Who’s out there?

932
00:58:34,171 --> 00:58:38,511
Well, well!
Is this your friend, Annie?

933
00:58:38,592 --> 00:58:40,752
Introduce me proper‐like.

934
00:58:42,470 --> 00:58:46,600
Lucy, this is my pa.
Pa, this is Lucy.

935
00:58:46,683 --> 00:58:48,553
LINUS: What you got there?
Pie.

936
00:58:48,685 --> 00:58:50,565
LINUS: Is that a fruit pie?

937
00:58:50,687 --> 00:58:53,397
Well, now, ain’t that nice?

938
00:58:53,523 --> 00:58:55,103
Well, come on in.

939
00:58:55,192 --> 00:58:59,862
We got some sweet water
would go good with it.
Mm‐mm.

940
00:58:59,988 --> 00:59:02,158
Well, let me see.

941
00:59:02,240 --> 00:59:04,080
We got some plates.

942
00:59:04,201 --> 00:59:06,501
Go over and get some cups,
Annie.

943
00:59:08,371 --> 00:59:10,241
Oh!

944
00:59:10,373 --> 00:59:11,543
Oh, I just thought...

945
00:59:11,666 --> 00:59:13,626
Annie, your mother
and brothers

946
00:59:13,710 --> 00:59:15,800
are up there on the ridge
pickin’ some berries.

947
00:59:15,879 --> 00:59:17,589
Why don’t you run up there
and fetch ’em?

948
00:59:17,714 --> 00:59:19,464
We can all have some pie.

949
00:59:20,300 --> 00:59:21,890
Go on and get ’em.

950
00:59:28,016 --> 00:59:31,936
Young lady,
won’t you please have a seat?

951
00:59:34,689 --> 00:59:38,159
I was a big‐game hunter
in California

952
00:59:38,235 --> 00:59:40,405
before there was
hardly a soul here.

953
00:59:41,363 --> 00:59:43,363
Everybody used to come
to my door.

954
00:59:43,448 --> 00:59:47,368
You should have seen it then.
Bountiful.

955
00:59:47,452 --> 00:59:50,412
All gone now.

956
00:59:50,497 --> 00:59:55,337
My eye got took out
by a grizzly.

957
00:59:55,418 --> 00:59:57,838
I did all right trappin’
for a while,

958
00:59:57,921 --> 01:00:03,051
till the damn gold miners
scared all the small game
away.

959
01:00:03,134 --> 01:00:04,594
Your pa,

960
01:00:05,929 --> 01:00:09,139
he a miner, girl?

961
01:00:09,266 --> 01:00:11,056
No, he’s dead.

962
01:00:11,142 --> 01:00:12,472
Oh.

963
01:00:12,602 --> 01:00:16,312
Well, that’s too bad.
Girl needs to have a pa.

964
01:00:16,439 --> 01:00:17,739
Yeah.

965
01:00:17,816 --> 01:00:20,736
Well, you sure are
a purty little thing.

966
01:00:20,819 --> 01:00:24,409
Your skin is so nice
and smooth,

967
01:00:24,489 --> 01:00:27,159
and your hair is so purty.

968
01:00:27,284 --> 01:00:28,324
Where you goin’, girl?

969
01:00:28,451 --> 01:00:29,451
[GRUNTS]

970
01:00:29,577 --> 01:00:31,117
[SCREAMS] Get off of me!

971
01:00:31,204 --> 01:00:32,374
[LINUS SCREAMS]

972
01:00:32,455 --> 01:00:34,285
Lucy! Lucy!
Go on, get out of here.

973
01:00:34,416 --> 01:00:36,296
BERNARD: Get out! Run!

974
01:00:36,376 --> 01:00:38,086
[YELLING]

975
01:00:39,462 --> 01:00:40,962
[GROANING]

976
01:00:43,300 --> 01:00:45,140
Good Lord, what have I done?

977
01:00:47,012 --> 01:00:49,052
You can’t tell no one
about this, Lucy.

978
01:00:49,139 --> 01:00:52,019
Pa’ll kill you
if he hear you do.
I know him.

979
01:00:54,978 --> 01:00:56,478
Annie!

980
01:00:58,481 --> 01:01:01,391
Did your pa
kill your sister, Annie?

981
01:01:01,484 --> 01:01:03,314
You can’t stay here.
You gotta come home with me.

982
01:01:03,445 --> 01:01:07,485
No, he’d find me.
I’ll stay in the woods.
I know places he don’t.

983
01:01:07,574 --> 01:01:09,784
In a few days, he’ll forget.

984
01:01:11,244 --> 01:01:12,824
[CRYING] He, uh...

985
01:01:12,954 --> 01:01:15,874
He...

986
01:01:15,999 --> 01:01:18,459
He hits Mama.

987
01:01:20,211 --> 01:01:22,751
She don’t hardly talk
no more.

988
01:01:25,175 --> 01:01:26,965
Will you come see me?

989
01:01:28,136 --> 01:01:29,216
You’ll come?

990
01:01:29,346 --> 01:01:31,766
I’ll come. I’ll come.

991
01:01:33,767 --> 01:01:35,647
This is the best I could do,
Bernard.

992
01:01:35,727 --> 01:01:38,017
Mr. Flagg would never think
to look for you here,

993
01:01:38,104 --> 01:01:41,234
and I know
how to shoot a shotgun
if he does.

994
01:01:41,358 --> 01:01:43,358
It’s just fine, Miss Lucy.

995
01:01:43,485 --> 01:01:47,485
I just ain’t never had
no one lookin’ out
for me before, that’s all.

996
01:01:47,572 --> 01:01:50,192
Well, I’ve never had anyone
save my life before.

997
01:01:56,623 --> 01:02:01,043
Bernard has decided
to stay in the shed
in case of forest fires.

998
01:02:10,845 --> 01:02:14,225
Yes, I would say
that you are workin’
much too hard.

999
01:02:14,349 --> 01:02:16,899
Would you let me please
just help you chop
a little bit of this?

1000
01:02:16,976 --> 01:02:19,186
Well, that’s very kind
of you, Mr. Claymore.

1001
01:02:19,270 --> 01:02:20,860
Clyde.

1002
01:02:20,939 --> 01:02:22,739
Clyde.

1003
01:02:22,857 --> 01:02:26,067
Thank you,
but I can’t pay you.

1004
01:02:26,152 --> 01:02:30,152
You know, I don’t offer
out of any charity

1005
01:02:30,240 --> 01:02:32,370
or for the hope of
any sort of future employment.

1006
01:02:32,450 --> 01:02:36,120
And can you not just accept
and swallow the fact
that I wanna help you,

1007
01:02:36,246 --> 01:02:38,126
plain and simple? Damn!

1008
01:02:44,045 --> 01:02:45,585
You made me swear.

1009
01:02:45,672 --> 01:02:47,712
Anything else?

1010
01:02:47,799 --> 01:02:48,929
No.

1011
01:02:51,594 --> 01:02:52,924
No.

1012
01:02:59,102 --> 01:03:01,182
[LAUGHING]

1013
01:03:01,271 --> 01:03:02,481
All right, step back.

1014
01:03:02,605 --> 01:03:04,065
I wouldn’t hold the bottom
of the ax.

1015
01:03:04,149 --> 01:03:06,239
That’s rather dangerous.
Oh, no, please, watch this.

1016
01:03:06,317 --> 01:03:07,737
[GRUNTING] If I can...

1017
01:03:07,819 --> 01:03:10,619
It’s a wonderful shot.

1018
01:03:10,697 --> 01:03:13,997
What’s goin’ on?
Someone’s been shot.

1019
01:03:14,117 --> 01:03:16,997
He’s got a bullet hole
in the back of his head.
Haul him out of there.

1020
01:03:17,120 --> 01:03:18,290
Who is he, Jonas?

1021
01:03:18,371 --> 01:03:21,081
Linus Flagg.
Somebody murdered him.

1022
01:03:33,344 --> 01:03:34,714
Annie?

1023
01:03:36,055 --> 01:03:39,305
Your pa is dead.
Somebody shot him.

1024
01:03:41,436 --> 01:03:43,016
He a varmint.

1025
01:03:49,944 --> 01:03:52,824
AMOS: Jonas,
the Sheriff’s comin’.

1026
01:03:57,327 --> 01:03:58,827
SCATTER: Deputy Scraggs.

1027
01:03:58,912 --> 01:04:01,072
They told me you found him
in the crick?

1028
01:04:01,164 --> 01:04:02,374
SCATTER: Yep.

1029
01:04:04,501 --> 01:04:06,091
I guess he’s a miner.

1030
01:04:06,169 --> 01:04:07,919
Nope, he was a trapper.

1031
01:04:09,005 --> 01:04:10,175
Huh.

1032
01:04:12,759 --> 01:04:15,679
Anybody see anything
or hear anything?

1033
01:04:18,097 --> 01:04:20,187
I guess maybe a woodpecker
could have done it.

1034
01:04:20,308 --> 01:04:22,768
If you ask me,
it was that nigger, Bernard.
He done it.

1035
01:04:22,852 --> 01:04:25,852
Bernard wouldn’t
harm anyone
and you know that, Snoose.

1036
01:04:25,939 --> 01:04:27,779
SCRAGGS: I’ll decide
who done the killin’.

1037
01:04:27,857 --> 01:04:29,697
This fella got a family?

1038
01:04:29,817 --> 01:04:31,197
They got a little place
up on Bottle Creek.

1039
01:04:31,277 --> 01:04:35,237
SCRAGGS: You show me
where that’s at?

1040
01:04:35,365 --> 01:04:39,075
Some of you gents ought
to bury this no‐neck stiff
before he draws flies.

1041
01:04:39,202 --> 01:04:41,662
It’s gonna get hot.

1042
01:04:41,746 --> 01:04:43,836
You don’t want to see this.

1043
01:04:45,833 --> 01:04:47,753
Aren’t you coming?

1044
01:04:49,045 --> 01:04:51,885
I may be needed
as a character witness.

1045
01:04:52,924 --> 01:04:55,424
She’s been reading
those law books.

1046
01:04:58,471 --> 01:05:01,051
AMOS: Looks like the Sheriff
arrested Flagg’s wife.

1047
01:05:01,140 --> 01:05:03,270
JIMMY: Did they bring
their young ’uns?

1048
01:05:05,895 --> 01:05:09,065
Annie! Annie?

1049
01:05:09,190 --> 01:05:12,950
Annie, if you don’t come
to the trial,
they’re gonna hang your mama.

1050
01:05:13,069 --> 01:05:14,199
Annie!

1051
01:05:21,119 --> 01:05:23,629
All right,
take your seats, please.
Take your seats, please.

1052
01:05:23,746 --> 01:05:26,666
I call this court to order.

1053
01:05:26,749 --> 01:05:30,589
Now, in the absence of a judge
and a prosecutor

1054
01:05:30,670 --> 01:05:32,010
and a defense lawyer,

1055
01:05:32,088 --> 01:05:35,718
I, Deputy Sheriff
Ambrose Scraggs,

1056
01:05:35,800 --> 01:05:38,640
I’ll serve as all three
of them myself.

1057
01:05:38,761 --> 01:05:40,761
Mrs. Flagg here
will be the first witness.

1058
01:05:40,847 --> 01:05:43,767
Mr. Claymore, will you
swear her in, please, sir?

1059
01:05:46,894 --> 01:05:49,934
You don’t, uh...
You don’t tell lies, do you?

1060
01:05:51,941 --> 01:05:53,731
You swear to God?

1061
01:05:55,945 --> 01:05:58,275
Mrs. Flagg,
did you murder your husband?

1062
01:05:59,782 --> 01:06:01,782
She’s guilty.
[ALL AGREEING]

1063
01:06:01,909 --> 01:06:03,209
Yeah, string her up!
Get rid of her!

1064
01:06:03,286 --> 01:06:05,746
SCRAGGS: Sit down and shut up,
all of you.

1065
01:06:05,830 --> 01:06:08,750
I’ll decide who’s guilty.

1066
01:06:08,833 --> 01:06:11,663
Why’d you shoot him,
Mrs. Flagg?
Was he doin’ somethin’ to you?

1067
01:06:11,794 --> 01:06:14,834
Was he doin’ somethin’
that provoked you
to killin’ him?

1068
01:06:14,964 --> 01:06:17,044
He was beatin’ on Ma
with a sycamore stick,

1069
01:06:17,133 --> 01:06:19,133
because they’re real hard
and they don’t break easy.

1070
01:06:19,260 --> 01:06:21,810
Everybody knows Linus
was a mean son of a bitch.

1071
01:06:21,888 --> 01:06:24,728
You don’t talk in this court
unless you’re a witness.

1072
01:06:24,807 --> 01:06:26,557
SCRAGGS: It ain’t evidence.
It’s hearsay.

1073
01:06:26,643 --> 01:06:29,353
Mrs. Flagg, take your seat.
And if there’s
no more witnesses...

1074
01:06:29,479 --> 01:06:33,399
I would like Mrs. Flagg
to demonstrate
her marksmanship, Your Honor.

1075
01:06:34,651 --> 01:06:36,821
[CHUCKLING] Who are you?

1076
01:06:36,944 --> 01:06:39,484
I’m Miss Lucy Whipple,

1077
01:06:40,823 --> 01:06:42,783
and I would like
to defend Mrs. Flagg.

1078
01:06:42,867 --> 01:06:44,827
[CROWD CHATTERING]

1079
01:06:44,911 --> 01:06:47,381
[LAUGHING]
You would, would you?

1080
01:06:47,497 --> 01:06:48,997
How old are you, daughter?

1081
01:06:49,123 --> 01:06:52,333
I was 14 on Sunday,
but no one remembered.

1082
01:06:53,753 --> 01:06:55,713
Now, Mrs. Flagg
has the right to a lawyer,

1083
01:06:55,838 --> 01:06:57,798
according to the laws
of California,

1084
01:06:57,882 --> 01:07:00,342
which became a state
September 9th.

1085
01:07:00,468 --> 01:07:01,848
I deeply volunteer.

1086
01:07:01,928 --> 01:07:04,428
You’re just a little ol’ girl.

1087
01:07:04,514 --> 01:07:07,594
Whatever would make you think
you could defend
a full‐grown woman

1088
01:07:07,684 --> 01:07:11,014
who’s, by the way,
already confessed
to the killin’?

1089
01:07:11,104 --> 01:07:13,734
There’s no age limit
in the law, Your Honor.

1090
01:07:13,856 --> 01:07:17,316
And I’ve read law books,
so I’m not entirely
uninformed.

1091
01:07:19,862 --> 01:07:23,442
All right. All right.
Go to it.

1092
01:07:23,533 --> 01:07:24,823
Let’s hear
what you got to say.

1093
01:07:24,909 --> 01:07:26,709
Lucy, what are you doing?

1094
01:07:26,828 --> 01:07:30,918
Mama, you said
every tub needs to stand
on its own bottom sometime.

1095
01:07:31,040 --> 01:07:33,050
Well, I’m standing.

1096
01:07:34,419 --> 01:07:36,879
Now, Your Honor,
if Mrs. Flagg shot Mr. Flagg,

1097
01:07:36,963 --> 01:07:39,423
then we need to demonstrate
how well she can shoot.

1098
01:07:39,549 --> 01:07:40,969
How are you gonna do that?

1099
01:07:41,050 --> 01:07:44,810
Uh, Mr. Scatter, can you
get me the rifle, please?

1100
01:07:44,887 --> 01:07:48,807
SCRAGGS:
But you be damn careful, lady.
You’ve already killed one man.

1101
01:07:48,891 --> 01:07:51,851
There ain’t no need
of killin’ any more.

1102
01:07:55,398 --> 01:07:59,068
Now, Mrs. Flagg,
do you think you can shoot
this mug right there?

1103
01:08:00,778 --> 01:08:02,078
[GUN COCKING]

1104
01:08:03,740 --> 01:08:05,620
[PEOPLE EXCLAIMING]

1105
01:08:07,452 --> 01:08:11,452
SNOOSE:
Damn, we’re losin’ beer.
Plug it up.

1106
01:08:11,581 --> 01:08:13,171
AMOS: I got it, I got it.

1107
01:08:13,249 --> 01:08:15,959
As you can see, Your Honor,
she’s very badly nearsighted.

1108
01:08:16,085 --> 01:08:18,335
So how could she
have shot her husband?

1109
01:08:18,421 --> 01:08:22,141
That was pretty clever.
Pretty dang clever.

1110
01:08:22,258 --> 01:08:24,258
But it don’t prove nothin’.

1111
01:08:24,343 --> 01:08:26,803
She could have missed that mug
on purpose.

1112
01:08:26,929 --> 01:08:29,729
I don’t care if she’s blind
as a bat, dearie.

1113
01:08:29,807 --> 01:08:33,937
She could have snuck up
behind her husband anytime
and just blasted away.

1114
01:08:34,020 --> 01:08:36,480
No, I think she shot him
point‐blank from the front

1115
01:08:36,606 --> 01:08:38,946
when he came after her
with a sycamore stick.

1116
01:08:39,025 --> 01:08:43,525
And I’ve seen that
same evidence of that stick
on his daughter, Annie.

1117
01:08:43,613 --> 01:08:45,983
Not evidence. That’s hearsay.

1118
01:08:47,950 --> 01:08:52,710
Well, he inflicted these
on me, Your Honor,

1119
01:08:52,789 --> 01:08:55,249
and that is not hearsay.

1120
01:08:56,667 --> 01:08:58,207
Damn.

1121
01:08:59,462 --> 01:09:00,962
SCRAGGS: I’m sorry.

1122
01:09:01,088 --> 01:09:03,088
But the fact remains,
you can’t be a defense lawyer

1123
01:09:03,174 --> 01:09:05,044
and a witness
in the same trial.

1124
01:09:05,134 --> 01:09:09,634
Now, the jury will just
disregard what you saw
and what she had to say.

1125
01:09:12,892 --> 01:09:14,642
Tell me this, Miss Whipple.

1126
01:09:14,769 --> 01:09:19,319
You say
Mrs. Flagg shot her husband
point‐blank from the front.

1127
01:09:20,608 --> 01:09:23,158
How come the bullet was able
to get around the back

1128
01:09:23,236 --> 01:09:24,736
and blow the back
of his neck off?

1129
01:09:24,821 --> 01:09:26,491
Have you got an answer
for that, dearie?

1130
01:09:26,572 --> 01:09:29,742
It ricocheted off the pots
and pans, Your Honor.

1131
01:09:29,826 --> 01:09:31,786
SCRAGGS:
They found him in the crick.

1132
01:09:31,869 --> 01:09:36,039
There ain’t no pots and pans
in the crick to ricochet
no bullets off of.

1133
01:09:36,165 --> 01:09:38,375
But it’s clear as cold water,
Your Honor,

1134
01:09:38,501 --> 01:09:42,301
that he was dragged
into that creek
after he was shot.

1135
01:09:42,380 --> 01:09:44,010
Now, as to the pots
and pans,

1136
01:09:44,131 --> 01:09:46,751
I will refer
to the extraordinary case

1137
01:09:46,843 --> 01:09:50,173
of Rattlesnake Jake,
a true murderer.

1138
01:09:50,304 --> 01:09:52,434
Now, when Jake
shot the Sheriff,

1139
01:09:52,515 --> 01:09:55,355
the bullet bounced
off the brass bar rail
and whizzed through the night,

1140
01:09:55,434 --> 01:09:57,684
where it hit a grizzly
about to devour a child.

1141
01:09:57,812 --> 01:10:01,522
Now, Jake lied and said
he was aiming for the grizzly
and not the Sheriff.

1142
01:10:01,649 --> 01:10:06,869
But Mrs. Flagg,
she aimed right for Mr. Flagg
in self‐defense.

1143
01:10:06,946 --> 01:10:08,866
And missed.

1144
01:10:08,990 --> 01:10:12,370
And the bullet ricocheted
off the pots and pans,
zinged around the room,

1145
01:10:12,493 --> 01:10:15,453
and hit Mr. Flagg
in the back of the neck.

1146
01:10:15,538 --> 01:10:19,048
And just like that,
he was dead
as a can of corned beef.

1147
01:10:19,166 --> 01:10:21,046
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

1148
01:10:21,168 --> 01:10:25,508
That’s poppycock.
I never heard nothin’
like that in all of my life.

1149
01:10:25,590 --> 01:10:27,930
I gave you the right
to defend this wretched woman,

1150
01:10:28,050 --> 01:10:32,730
not to make a mockery
out of this court
and her justice.

1151
01:10:32,805 --> 01:10:36,145
Now, dearie,
you get over there
and you sit down and hush.

1152
01:10:43,399 --> 01:10:47,069
The woman freely confessed
to murder.

1153
01:10:47,194 --> 01:10:50,824
I don’t give a hang
if she’s as blind as a bat.

1154
01:10:50,907 --> 01:10:53,077
I say she snuck up
behind her husband

1155
01:10:53,159 --> 01:10:57,419
and killed him in cold blood
like a low‐down coward.

1156
01:10:57,538 --> 01:10:59,588
She’s gonna hang by the neck
till she’s dead.

1157
01:10:59,707 --> 01:11:02,087
[ALL MURMURING]

1158
01:11:03,002 --> 01:11:04,412
What is it now?

1159
01:11:06,088 --> 01:11:08,178
A verdict of murder
may be rendered

1160
01:11:08,257 --> 01:11:11,847
only if there is unanimous
agreement among the jurors,

1161
01:11:11,928 --> 01:11:13,268
who have examined the evidence

1162
01:11:13,346 --> 01:11:15,886
and concluded
beyond a reasonable doubt

1163
01:11:15,973 --> 01:11:17,643
that the defendant is guilty.

1164
01:11:17,767 --> 01:11:20,767
Your Honor,
the Statutes of California.

1165
01:11:20,895 --> 01:11:25,065
Now,
there’s not enough evidence
to prove that she killed him

1166
01:11:25,149 --> 01:11:26,699
or she didn’t kill him.

1167
01:11:26,776 --> 01:11:29,986
So there is reasonable doubt.

1168
01:11:30,112 --> 01:11:33,402
And that’s all
I’m trying to say.

1169
01:11:36,160 --> 01:11:37,620
All right.

1170
01:11:39,497 --> 01:11:43,457
Everybody in the jury
that’s for conviction,
raise up your hands.

1171
01:11:49,256 --> 01:11:52,046
The jury’s hung
higher than a dead pig
at Christmastime.

1172
01:11:52,134 --> 01:11:54,174
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

1173
01:11:54,303 --> 01:11:55,673
She’s free, Annie.

1174
01:11:55,805 --> 01:11:57,095
Yeah!

1175
01:11:57,181 --> 01:12:00,801
Mrs. Flagg, you can go home.

1176
01:12:02,144 --> 01:12:03,934
Mr. Scatter,
can we open this bar?

1177
01:12:04,021 --> 01:12:06,141
[ALL CHEERING]

1178
01:12:11,821 --> 01:12:14,371
Well done, dearie.

1179
01:12:14,490 --> 01:12:15,700
Thank you.

1180
01:12:21,497 --> 01:12:22,707
Hey.

1181
01:12:24,166 --> 01:12:27,166
Your pa
had the devil in him,

1182
01:12:28,254 --> 01:12:33,094
and what happened
was God’s justice,

1183
01:12:33,175 --> 01:12:34,715
you hear me?

1184
01:12:38,973 --> 01:12:42,013
I’m grateful
for all your doings, Lucy,
but it ain’t right.

1185
01:12:42,143 --> 01:12:43,803
It is so.

1186
01:12:43,894 --> 01:12:48,024
Your pa would have
killed you, your ma
and your brothers.

1187
01:12:48,107 --> 01:12:50,487
[WHISPERING]
Annie, you had to shoot him.

1188
01:12:51,402 --> 01:12:53,612
You knew I shot him?

1189
01:12:56,532 --> 01:13:00,572
[STAMMERING]
And you don’t feel guilty
before God about lyin’?

1190
01:13:00,703 --> 01:13:02,493
I ain’t lyin’.

1191
01:13:02,580 --> 01:13:06,300
I just said
I couldn’t prove the truth.

1192
01:13:06,375 --> 01:13:09,665
I mean, you took one life
to save another.

1193
01:13:13,049 --> 01:13:15,009
What happened
with Mr. Flagg?

1194
01:13:15,092 --> 01:13:17,002
Well, he didn’t have time
to do much.

1195
01:13:17,094 --> 01:13:20,344
Annie fetched Bernard
and then he laid him out
like a side of beef.

1196
01:13:20,431 --> 01:13:21,521
Why didn’t you tell me?

1197
01:13:21,599 --> 01:13:24,269
Because you have
a big temper, Mama,

1198
01:13:24,393 --> 01:13:26,183
and you would have
blown his head off

1199
01:13:26,270 --> 01:13:29,320
and then you would have
gone to jail for 150 years,
that’s why.

1200
01:13:29,398 --> 01:13:31,398
That’s probably true.

1201
01:13:35,863 --> 01:13:38,283
It’s also true

1202
01:13:38,407 --> 01:13:40,997
that Mrs. Flagg
would be hanging
from a tree right now

1203
01:13:41,077 --> 01:13:42,667
if it wasn’t for you.

1204
01:13:44,080 --> 01:13:47,210
Reading books
did some real good.

1205
01:13:47,291 --> 01:13:51,331
So from now on,

1206
01:13:51,420 --> 01:13:55,850
I think you should take
two hours every day
for reading.

1207
01:13:55,925 --> 01:13:57,715
Thank you, Mama.

1208
01:13:57,802 --> 01:14:01,222
That doesn’t mean three hours
or that you don’t
do your chores.

1209
01:14:02,640 --> 01:14:06,060
I’m sorry for forgetting
your birthday, Lucy.

1210
01:14:06,143 --> 01:14:08,183
I’m proud of you.

1211
01:14:08,270 --> 01:14:10,440
I am indeed.

1212
01:14:14,777 --> 01:14:15,777
[SNIFFING]

1213
01:14:16,946 --> 01:14:19,196
I smell smoke.

1214
01:14:19,281 --> 01:14:20,821
Do you smell it?

1215
01:14:26,288 --> 01:14:27,918
Fire!
Fire!

1216
01:14:27,998 --> 01:14:29,208
Fire!

1217
01:14:29,291 --> 01:14:30,951
BOTH: Fire!

1218
01:14:35,047 --> 01:14:37,137
[ALL SHOUTING]

1219
01:14:37,216 --> 01:14:40,136
Get a bucket for me!
Get a bucket for me!

1220
01:14:40,219 --> 01:14:41,809
Get going!

1221
01:14:41,887 --> 01:14:43,767
Take this. Take it.

1222
01:14:46,183 --> 01:14:49,973
SCATTER:
To the right, to the right!
Go! Go to the main tank!

1223
01:14:51,230 --> 01:14:53,320
These buckets are empty!

1224
01:14:55,901 --> 01:14:57,561
AMOS: We need more water!

1225
01:15:00,322 --> 01:15:01,532
MAN: Faster!

1226
01:15:03,826 --> 01:15:05,746
The store! The store!

1227
01:15:06,912 --> 01:15:08,282
SCATTER: To the store!

1228
01:15:09,957 --> 01:15:10,877
AMOS: All of you!

1229
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:13,050
Give me a bucket.

1230
01:15:13,169 --> 01:15:15,009
AMOS: It’s gettin’
the boardinghouse!

1231
01:15:16,130 --> 01:15:17,760
ARVELLA: Go and get Prairie.

1232
01:15:19,216 --> 01:15:20,846
Be careful.

1233
01:15:20,968 --> 01:15:22,518
Prairie, get up.

1234
01:15:22,595 --> 01:15:24,055
Quickly, quickly. Prairie!

1235
01:15:27,057 --> 01:15:29,187
Take her.
Yeah, I got her.

1236
01:15:29,310 --> 01:15:31,020
All right, come on,
we gotta go.

1237
01:15:31,103 --> 01:15:32,683
Lucy.
ARVELLA: Come on.

1238
01:15:38,485 --> 01:15:41,985
We need the buckets
goddamn faster. Faster!

1239
01:15:42,072 --> 01:15:43,782
Here, take the baby.

1240
01:15:45,576 --> 01:15:47,616
You be careful.
You be careful.

1241
01:15:48,871 --> 01:15:51,041
I’m on fire! Hey!

1242
01:15:51,123 --> 01:15:53,623
You’re all right.
You’re all right.

1243
01:15:55,127 --> 01:15:56,917
Oh, jeez!

1244
01:16:06,764 --> 01:16:09,434
MAN: The trees!
Head for the trees!

1245
01:16:17,775 --> 01:16:20,195
Sad mornin’.

1246
01:16:20,277 --> 01:16:22,237
This town’s gone.

1247
01:16:22,363 --> 01:16:23,693
God took it.

1248
01:16:23,781 --> 01:16:26,201
Yeah, it’s finished,
sure enough. Wiped out.

1249
01:16:26,283 --> 01:16:29,493
We ain’t had nothin’
but bad luck
since you came into town.

1250
01:16:29,578 --> 01:16:30,918
It started near your shed.

1251
01:16:31,038 --> 01:16:32,498
I’m startin’ to think
you’re like a Jonas,

1252
01:16:32,581 --> 01:16:33,911
bringin’ hard times.

1253
01:16:33,999 --> 01:16:36,419
It wasn’t Bernard.
I kicked over a lantern.

1254
01:16:37,795 --> 01:16:40,425
An accident,
pure and simple,

1255
01:16:40,506 --> 01:16:42,796
and I’m awful sorry.

1256
01:16:42,925 --> 01:16:44,845
Oh, so, what?

1257
01:16:44,927 --> 01:16:47,977
This town wasn’t nothin’
to begin with.

1258
01:16:49,265 --> 01:16:51,095
Ashes to ashes.

1259
01:16:51,225 --> 01:16:54,395
"Ashes to ashes"!

1260
01:16:54,478 --> 01:16:57,318
So the town burned down.
Does that mean
we’re supposed to give up?

1261
01:16:57,439 --> 01:17:01,449
Well, I don’t give up.
Not me.

1262
01:17:01,527 --> 01:17:03,617
You try, you fail,
you try again.

1263
01:17:03,696 --> 01:17:06,326
I set up home here,
and I’m stayin’ here.

1264
01:17:06,448 --> 01:17:09,408
You folks can do
whatever the hell you want.

1265
01:17:15,958 --> 01:17:17,298
I’ll stay too.

1266
01:17:17,418 --> 01:17:20,338
MAN: I got no place else
to go.

1267
01:17:20,462 --> 01:17:22,172
ARVELLA: Seems like
Butte’s really gone.

1268
01:17:22,298 --> 01:17:26,888
We don’t have
a shirt or a shoe
to remember him by.

1269
01:17:26,969 --> 01:17:30,809
Well, maybe it’s time
we go back to Massachusetts,
Mama.

1270
01:17:35,436 --> 01:17:38,476
Mama, I found Butte’s whistle.

1271
01:17:40,065 --> 01:17:41,195
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

1272
01:17:43,485 --> 01:17:44,985
Good girl.

1273
01:17:51,910 --> 01:17:54,080
LUCY: <i>Lucky Diggins is gone,</i>

1274
01:17:54,163 --> 01:17:56,493
<i>burned to ashes in 33 minutes.</i>

1275
01:17:56,623 --> 01:17:58,703
<i>A lot of the miners
are leaving.</i>

1276
01:17:58,834 --> 01:18:01,164
<i>The only good thing
</i> <i>that happened
is from a bad thing.</i>

1277
01:18:01,253 --> 01:18:05,383
<i>Jimmy Whiskers found
a 13‐pound nugget of gold
in the ashes.</i>

1278
01:18:05,507 --> 01:18:08,467
<i>Lucky Jim. Unlucky Diggins.</i>

1279
01:18:09,845 --> 01:18:12,055
You’re not leaving,
are you, Bernard?

1280
01:18:13,640 --> 01:18:15,690
Reckon I am, Missus.

1281
01:18:15,809 --> 01:18:19,189
Uh, I was talkin’
to that fella,
that Jed there,

1282
01:18:19,271 --> 01:18:22,561
and, uh, he told me about
these fellas, lawyers,
in San Francisco.

1283
01:18:22,691 --> 01:18:25,311
Help a colored man like me
get free of slavery.

1284
01:18:25,402 --> 01:18:27,442
I’m gonna be free.
Legal free.

1285
01:18:27,529 --> 01:18:29,829
I wish I was free.

1286
01:18:29,907 --> 01:18:32,367
But it seems like
I’m stuck here like mud.

1287
01:18:32,493 --> 01:18:36,993
Miss Lucy, now, it could be
that here’s where
you’s supposed to be stuck.

1288
01:18:38,499 --> 01:18:40,709
Godspeed to you, Miss Lucy.

1289
01:18:51,678 --> 01:18:53,848
I don’t know what to do.

1290
01:18:55,516 --> 01:18:57,726
Why does everything
have to change?

1291
01:18:57,810 --> 01:19:00,610
Why can’t life
just stay the same?

1292
01:19:00,729 --> 01:19:03,149
MR. WHIPPLE:
<i>It wouldn’t be life if it did.</i>

1293
01:19:07,403 --> 01:19:09,023
Papa!

1294
01:19:09,113 --> 01:19:11,573
<i>What if you had your wish
and nothing changed?</i>

1295
01:19:11,698 --> 01:19:15,408
<i>Then nothing would grow,
not even you.</i>

1296
01:19:15,494 --> 01:19:17,664
<i>And I wouldn’t want that.</i>

1297
01:19:17,746 --> 01:19:20,036
<i>Change is a gift, Lucy.</i>

1298
01:19:26,588 --> 01:19:28,138
Papa!

1299
01:19:29,383 --> 01:19:30,753
Papa?

1300
01:19:36,181 --> 01:19:37,591
Papa.

1301
01:19:42,062 --> 01:19:45,852
Now, what do you think
the good Lord has planned
for us now?

1302
01:19:45,941 --> 01:19:49,191
We’ve been through the fire.
Maybe the flood.

1303
01:19:51,530 --> 01:19:55,790
Week before the fire,
I was pickin’ berries
up at Calico Meadow,

1304
01:19:55,868 --> 01:19:59,118
and there were
all these butterflies.

1305
01:19:59,204 --> 01:20:01,164
They were yellow and blue

1306
01:20:02,374 --> 01:20:05,124
and like a carpet.

1307
01:20:05,210 --> 01:20:09,590
And never before had I seen
more evidence of God,

1308
01:20:09,673 --> 01:20:12,343
like God’s palette.

1309
01:20:12,468 --> 01:20:16,848
And as I watched,
I thought to myself,
I said,

1310
01:20:18,348 --> 01:20:21,268
"Arvella’s more alive
than all these butterflies.

1311
01:20:23,228 --> 01:20:24,728
"She’s more real.

1312
01:20:28,484 --> 01:20:31,194
She’s more beautiful."

1313
01:20:31,320 --> 01:20:32,410
[LAUGHS]

1314
01:20:32,488 --> 01:20:34,658
This was my favorite pan.

1315
01:20:57,012 --> 01:20:58,342
[SIGHS]

1316
01:21:00,516 --> 01:21:02,436
Thank God
he brought you here.

1317
01:21:02,518 --> 01:21:03,858
Amen.

1318
01:21:09,816 --> 01:21:11,566
The question is that

1319
01:21:11,693 --> 01:21:15,773
if he wants me to go...

1320
01:21:18,742 --> 01:21:22,662
will you come with me?

1321
01:21:32,631 --> 01:21:35,261
Seems like a lot of people
are moving on.

1322
01:21:37,219 --> 01:21:38,889
Leaving Lucky Diggins.

1323
01:21:39,012 --> 01:21:41,512
Well, who wants to live
in filthy ashes, Mama?

1324
01:21:41,598 --> 01:21:44,728
I thought we’d come
and stay here forever,

1325
01:21:44,851 --> 01:21:46,431
but now I know
that my heart’s desire

1326
01:21:46,562 --> 01:21:50,392
is to always see
what’s on the other side
of the mountain.

1327
01:21:50,524 --> 01:21:52,944
Where are we going, Mama?

1328
01:21:53,068 --> 01:21:54,198
Well...

1329
01:21:55,612 --> 01:21:57,152
that depends.

1330
01:21:58,574 --> 01:22:00,444
Clyde is leaving.

1331
01:22:00,576 --> 01:22:02,036
He’s going
to the Sandwich Islands

1332
01:22:02,119 --> 01:22:03,749
to be a missionary
to the natives there,

1333
01:22:03,870 --> 01:22:05,580
and he wants us
to go with him.

1334
01:22:05,706 --> 01:22:07,706
You and me and Prairie.

1335
01:22:08,709 --> 01:22:11,419
The Sandwich Islands?
Yes.

1336
01:22:11,545 --> 01:22:13,585
You can’t be serious, Mama.

1337
01:22:13,672 --> 01:22:15,922
Where are
the Sandwich Islands?

1338
01:22:16,008 --> 01:22:18,808
And why would he want us
to go with him?

1339
01:22:19,928 --> 01:22:22,308
He’s asked me to be his wife.

1340
01:22:25,100 --> 01:22:26,360
His wife?

1341
01:22:31,273 --> 01:22:33,733
But you don’t even
like preachers.

1342
01:22:33,817 --> 01:22:35,527
But Clyde is different.

1343
01:22:35,611 --> 01:22:38,451
He’s a seeker and he’s good
and he’s kind.

1344
01:22:38,530 --> 01:22:41,750
And I think that, with time,
I could come to love him.

1345
01:22:44,661 --> 01:22:47,831
If you knew
I wanted to be safe,

1346
01:22:47,956 --> 01:22:50,876
why would you drag me off
to some remote island

1347
01:22:50,959 --> 01:22:53,919
with murdering savages?
We will be safe.

1348
01:22:54,004 --> 01:22:55,504
Clyde will make a fine father.

1349
01:22:55,631 --> 01:22:58,971
He loves you and he’ll
protect you.
I had a father!

1350
01:22:59,092 --> 01:23:02,012
And you have forgotten him,
and I haven’t.

1351
01:23:02,137 --> 01:23:04,307
That is not true.
Neither have I.

1352
01:23:09,645 --> 01:23:12,645
Go to the Sandwich Islands.

1353
01:23:12,731 --> 01:23:14,321
But I won’t.

1354
01:23:14,399 --> 01:23:16,279
I won’t go, either.

1355
01:23:20,197 --> 01:23:21,367
[SIGHING]

1356
01:23:33,335 --> 01:23:35,255
Is this rock taken?

1357
01:23:35,337 --> 01:23:36,377
No.

1358
01:23:39,966 --> 01:23:41,636
So I heard the stagecoach

1359
01:23:41,718 --> 01:23:44,638
is comin’ through
Rabbit Creek next week,
goin’ east.

1360
01:23:44,721 --> 01:23:46,631
I’m gonna be on it.

1361
01:23:46,723 --> 01:23:48,303
Do you wanna go?

1362
01:23:51,186 --> 01:23:53,026
Yes.

1363
01:23:53,105 --> 01:23:54,985
But I don’t think
I have enough money.

1364
01:23:55,065 --> 01:23:58,855
I do.
I made a lot of money here.

1365
01:23:58,944 --> 01:24:01,404
My corset is my bank.

1366
01:24:03,699 --> 01:24:05,539
But I’m pregnant,
so I’m quittin’.

1367
01:24:07,119 --> 01:24:09,039
Well, are you getting married?

1368
01:24:09,121 --> 01:24:10,381
No.

1369
01:24:10,455 --> 01:24:13,165
But I’m gonna say I was
and he died in a fire.

1370
01:24:14,876 --> 01:24:18,466
But my critter’s gonna
be born on the trip,
so I’ll need help.

1371
01:24:19,756 --> 01:24:22,256
If you’ll do it,
I’ll pay your way.

1372
01:24:25,220 --> 01:24:26,310
Yes.

1373
01:24:26,388 --> 01:24:27,558
Really? Yeah?

1374
01:24:28,557 --> 01:24:30,477
Deal?
Deal.

1375
01:24:32,352 --> 01:24:35,142
No, you may not go back
with Sophie Meagan,
and that is that.

1376
01:24:35,230 --> 01:24:37,900
Mama, I ran the boardinghouse
when you were sick.

1377
01:24:38,024 --> 01:24:39,814
I can live in the forest
if I need to.

1378
01:24:39,901 --> 01:24:41,731
I can take care
of Sophie’s baby.

1379
01:24:41,820 --> 01:24:45,290
Now, going west again
is Brother Clyde’s dream
and yours,

1380
01:24:45,407 --> 01:24:47,407
not mine.

1381
01:24:47,534 --> 01:24:48,704
I’m going home.

1382
01:24:48,785 --> 01:24:50,245
You’re just a child.

1383
01:24:50,328 --> 01:24:52,328
I’m 14, Mama.

1384
01:24:53,832 --> 01:24:57,252
Now, go find
your heart’s desire
and let me find mine.

1385
01:24:57,377 --> 01:25:01,257
She’s a strong, smart girl.
She’s gonna make
a fine woman.

1386
01:25:15,061 --> 01:25:17,601
I hope my biscuits and pies
weren’t that bad.

1387
01:25:17,731 --> 01:25:19,531
MAN: They were good, hon.

1388
01:25:19,608 --> 01:25:24,828
I wish I never said
you don’t have souls,
’cause I was dead wrong.

1389
01:25:24,946 --> 01:25:27,906
And I’ll miss you all
horribly.

1390
01:25:27,991 --> 01:25:29,611
[LUCY SIGHS]

1391
01:25:32,245 --> 01:25:35,335
Now, don’t talk back to Mama
like I did, okay?

1392
01:25:35,457 --> 01:25:37,127
I won’t, Lucy.

1393
01:25:38,293 --> 01:25:39,503
Love you.

1394
01:25:45,342 --> 01:25:49,052
Brother Claymore,
I’ve been thinking.

1395
01:25:50,722 --> 01:25:51,882
[SIGHS]

1396
01:25:51,973 --> 01:25:54,553
I love my real pa,

1397
01:25:54,643 --> 01:25:58,603
but if I can’t have
my real one,

1398
01:25:59,856 --> 01:26:01,446
then I’d rather you
than anyone.

1399
01:26:01,525 --> 01:26:04,605
That’s about the nicest thing
you could’ve said to me.

1400
01:26:05,904 --> 01:26:07,444
So take care of them.

1401
01:26:08,740 --> 01:26:11,370
Well, between God and me
and your daddy in heaven,

1402
01:26:11,493 --> 01:26:14,113
there’s nothin’
that’s gonna happen to them.

1403
01:26:18,542 --> 01:26:20,042
I’ll miss you.

1404
01:26:21,169 --> 01:26:23,299
We’ll see each other again.

1405
01:26:24,381 --> 01:26:27,471
We’ve got to,
because we’re family.

1406
01:26:30,011 --> 01:26:32,381
I want you
to have this locket.

1407
01:26:34,391 --> 01:26:35,561
Mama.

1408
01:26:38,353 --> 01:26:39,683
I love you.

1409
01:26:43,066 --> 01:26:44,526
[SNIFFLING]

1410
01:26:45,986 --> 01:26:47,526
I love you too.

1411
01:27:00,041 --> 01:27:01,541
Goodbye, all.

1412
01:27:01,668 --> 01:27:04,338
Bye‐bye.
So long, darlin’.
We’ll sure miss you.

1413
01:27:05,463 --> 01:27:06,503
[SIGHS]

1414
01:27:12,053 --> 01:27:13,303
[SIGHS]

1415
01:27:21,688 --> 01:27:23,318
Bye.
Goodbye.

1416
01:27:33,450 --> 01:27:34,750
You all right?

1417
01:27:52,886 --> 01:27:54,926
Mama?

1418
01:27:55,013 --> 01:27:57,093
PRAIRIE: Mama, look.

1419
01:27:57,182 --> 01:27:59,342
[♪]

1420
01:28:18,912 --> 01:28:20,072
You were right, Mama.

1421
01:28:20,163 --> 01:28:22,283
You told me
to follow my heart,

1422
01:28:22,374 --> 01:28:24,664
and my heart is yelling at me
to stay,

1423
01:28:24,793 --> 01:28:27,623
so I’m staying here,

1424
01:28:27,754 --> 01:28:33,134
in godforsaken, burnt‐out,
washed‐up Lucky Diggins.

1425
01:28:33,218 --> 01:28:35,718
[ALL CHEERING]

1426
01:28:35,804 --> 01:28:37,844
And I’m gonna need
a library,

1427
01:28:37,973 --> 01:28:40,553
because that’s
my heart’s desire.

1428
01:28:40,642 --> 01:28:43,142
So I’m staying put.

1429
01:28:44,312 --> 01:28:47,312
My goodness,
but you are mule‐stubborn.

1430
01:28:48,858 --> 01:28:50,698
Just like you, Mama.

1431
01:28:57,325 --> 01:28:59,535
LUCY: <i>Dear Mama, Clyde
and Prairie,</i>

1432
01:28:59,661 --> 01:29:02,001
<i>we’re rebuilding the town
with a new boardinghouse</i>

1433
01:29:02,080 --> 01:29:04,460
<i>and a real library.</i>

1434
01:29:04,541 --> 01:29:06,591
Mr. Scatter,
will you make sure
this roof doesn’t leak?

1435
01:29:06,668 --> 01:29:08,048
We don’t want the books
to get wet.

1436
01:29:08,169 --> 01:29:09,469
We will.

1437
01:29:09,546 --> 01:29:11,506
Lucy, I want my boys
to learn to read.

1438
01:29:11,631 --> 01:29:15,881
Miss Lucy,
I believe this sign
will go real nice here.

1439
01:29:16,011 --> 01:29:17,351
It’s wonderful.
Yes, ma’am.

1440
01:29:17,470 --> 01:29:19,520
Maybe you could have classes.

1441
01:29:19,639 --> 01:29:23,479
I know a fistful of miners
who might sign up.

1442
01:29:23,560 --> 01:29:25,150
LUCY: <i>The miners all pay
a dollar a month</i>

1443
01:29:25,228 --> 01:29:26,478
<i>to run the library,</i>

1444
01:29:26,563 --> 01:29:28,683
<i>and pay me,
the head librarian.</i>

1445
01:29:28,815 --> 01:29:30,855
<i>We already have 81 books.</i>

1446
01:29:30,942 --> 01:29:33,312
<i>New folks arrive every week.</i>

1447
01:29:33,403 --> 01:29:35,573
<i>I miss you all horribly,</i>

1448
01:29:35,697 --> 01:29:39,787
<i>but you were right all along
to bring us here, Mama.</i>

1449
01:29:39,868 --> 01:29:41,498
<i>Thank you.</i>

1450
01:29:41,578 --> 01:29:45,378
<i>Your loving daughter,
Miss Lucy Whipple, librarian</i>

1451
01:29:45,498 --> 01:29:48,338
<i>and heart’s‐contented citizen
of Lucky Diggins,</i>

1452
01:29:48,418 --> 01:29:50,838
<i>where things change every day.</i>

1453
01:29:54,090 --> 01:29:56,390
[♪]

